# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ammonia
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] The study of abiogenesis aims to determine how pre-life chemical reactions gave rise to life under conditions strikingly different from those on Earth today.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] It uses tools from biology and chemistry, attempting a synthesis of many sciences.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Life functions through the chemistry of carbon and water, and builds on four chemical families: lipids for cell membranes, carbohydrates such as sugars, amino acids for protein metabolism, and the nucleic acids DNA and RNA for heredity.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] A theory of abiogenesis must explain the origins and interactions of these classes of molecules.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Many approaches investigate how self-replicating molecules came into existence.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Researchers think that life descends from an RNA world, although other self-replicating and self-catalyzing molecules may have preceded RNA.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Other approaches ("metabolism-first" hypotheses) focus on how catalysis on the early Earth might have provided the precursor molecules for self-replication.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] The 1952 Miller–Urey experiment demonstrated that amino acids can be synthesized from inorganic compounds under conditions like early Earth's.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Subsequently, amino acids have been found in meteorites, comets, asteroids, and star-forming regions of space.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] While the last universal common ancestor of all modern organisms (LUCA) existed millions of years after the origin of life, its study can guide research into early universal characteristics.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] A genomics approach has sought to characterize LUCA by identifying the genes shared by Archaea and Bacteria, major branches of life.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] It appears there are 60 proteins common to all life and 355 prokaryotic genes that trace to LUCA; their functions imply that LUCA was anaerobic with the Wood–Ljungdahl pathway, deriving energy by chemiosmosis, and used DNA, the genetic code, and ribosomes.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Earlier cells might have had a leaky membrane and been powered by a naturally occurring proton gradient near a deep-sea white smoker hydrothermal vent; or, life may have originated inside the continental crust or in water at Earth's surface.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth is the only place known to harbor life, astrobiologists assume that life exists and came into being by similar processes on other planets.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Geochemical and fossil evidence informs most studies.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] The Earth was formed at 4.54 Gya, and the earliest evidence of life on Earth dates from 3.8 Gya from Western Australia.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Fossil micro-organisms may have lived in hydrothermal vent precipitates from Quebec, soon after ocean formation during the Hadean, so the process appears to have been relatively rapid in terms of geological time.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Life consists of reproduction with (heritable) variations.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] That in turn implies a suite of cellular machinery including messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Those proteins included enzymes to operate its anaerobic respiration via the Wood–Ljungdahl metabolic pathway, and a DNA polymerase to replicate its genetic material.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] The challenge for origin of life researchers is to explain how such a complex and tightly interlinked system could develop by evolutionary steps, as at first sight all its parts are necessary to enable it to function.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] For example, a cell, whether the LUCA or in a modern organism, copies its DNA with the DNA polymerase enzyme, which is itself produced by translating the DNA polymerase gene in the DNA.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Neither the enzyme nor the DNA can be produced without the other.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] The evolutionary process could have started with molecular self-replication, self-assembly such as of cell membranes, and autocatalysis via RNA ribozymes in an RNA world environment.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] The transition of non-life to life has not been observed experimentally.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Some scientists see both life and the origin of life as aspects of the same process.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] The preconditions to the development of a living cell like the LUCA are known, though disputed in detail: a habitable world is formed with a supply of minerals and liquid water and sources of free energy inflows such as our Sun and geothermal heat.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic synthesis creates a range of simple organic compounds, which are assembled into polymers such as proteins and RNA.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] On the other side, the process after the LUCA is readily understood: biological evolution caused the development of a wide range of species with varied forms and biochemical capabilities.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] However, the derivation of the LUCA from simple components is far from understood.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth remains the only place where life is known, the science of astrobiology seeks evidence of life on other planets.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] The advent of such polymers was most likely a critical step in prebiotic chemical evolution.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Those polymers derived, in turn, from simple organic compounds such as nucleobases, amino acids, and sugars, likely formed by reactions in the environment.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] A successful theory of the origin of life must explain how all these chemicals came into being.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] One ancient view of the origin of life, from Aristotle until the 19th century, was of spontaneous generation.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] This held that "lower" animals such as insects were generated by decaying organic substances, and that life arose by chance.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] This was questioned from the 17th century, in works like Thomas Browne's *Pseudodoxia Epidemica*.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] In 1665, Robert Hooke published the first drawings of a microorganism.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] In 1676, Antonie van Leeuwenhoek drew and described microorganisms, probably protozoa and bacteria.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Van Leeuwenhoek disagreed with spontaneous generation, and by the 1680s convinced himself, using experiments ranging from sealed and open meat incubation and the close study of insect reproduction, that the theory was incorrect.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] In 1668 Francesco Redi showed that no maggots appeared in meat when flies were prevented from laying eggs.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] By the middle of the 19th century, spontaneous generation was considered disproven.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Dating back to Anaxagoras in the 5th century BC, panspermia is the idea that life originated elsewhere in the universe and came to Earth.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] The modern version of panspermia holds that life may have been distributed to Earth by meteoroids, asteroids, comets or planetoids.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] This shifts the origin of life to another heavenly body.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] The advantage is that life is not required to have formed on each planet it occurs on, but in a more limited set of locations, and then spread about the galaxy to other star systems.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] There is some interest in the possibility that life originated on Mars and later transferred to Earth.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] The idea that life originated from non-living matter in slow stages appeared in Herbert Spencer's 1864–1867 book *Principles of Biology*, and in William Turner Thiselton-Dyer's 1879 paper "On spontaneous generation and evolution".
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane in 1929 proposed that the earliest cells slowly self-organized from a primordial soup, the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane suggested that the Earth's prebiotic oceans consisted of a "hot dilute soup" in which organic compounds could have formed.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Bernal showed that such mechanisms could form most of the necessary molecules for life from inorganic precursors.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] In 1967, he suggested three "stages": the origin of biological monomers; the origin of biological polymers; and the evolution from molecules to cells.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] In 1952, Stanley Miller and Harold Urey carried out a chemical experiment to demonstrate how organic molecules could have formed spontaneously from inorganic precursors under prebiotic conditions like those posited by the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] It passed an electric current through a highly reducing (lacking oxygen) mixture of gases—methane, ammonia, and hydrogen, with water vapor—to form organic monomers such as amino acids.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] The addition of iron and carbonate minerals, present in early oceans, produces a diverse array of amino acids.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Later work has focused on two other potential reducing environments: outer space and deep-sea hydrothermal vents.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after the Big Bang, roughly 14 Gya, the only chemical elements present in the universe were hydrogen, helium, and lithium, the three lightest atoms in the periodic table.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] These elements gradually condensed into vast clouds of gas, which collapsed under gravity into rotating protostellar disks.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Gravitational accretion of material at the hot and dense centers of these disks formed the first stars by the fusion of hydrogen.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Early stars were massive and short-lived, producing all the heavier elements by stellar nucleosynthesis.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Such element formation proceeds to its most stable element Iron-56.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Heavier elements were formed during supernovas at the end of a star's lifecycle.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon, currently the fourth most abundant element in the universe, was formed mainly in white dwarf stars.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] As these stars reached the end of their lifecycles, they ejected heavier elements, including carbon and oxygen, throughout the universe.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] These allowed for the formation of rocky planets.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] According to the nebular hypothesis, the Solar System began to form 4.6 Gya with the gravitational collapse of part of a giant molecular cloud.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Most of the collapsing mass collected in the center, forming the Sun, while the rest flattened into a protoplanetary disk out of which the planets formed.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] The age of the Earth is 4.54 Gya as found by radiometric dating of calcium-aluminium-rich inclusions in carbonaceous chrondrite meteorites, the oldest material in the Solar System.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Earth, during the Hadean eon (from its formation until 4.031 Gya,) was at first inhospitable to life.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] During its formation, the Earth lost much of its initial mass, and so lacked the gravity to hold molecular hydrogen and the bulk of the original inert gases.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after initial accretion of Earth at 4.48 Gya, its collision with Theia, a hypothesised impactor, is thought to have created the ejected debris that eventually formed the Moon.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] This impact removed the Earth's primary atmosphere, leaving behind clouds of viscous silicates and carbon dioxide.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] This unstable atmosphere was short-lived, soon condensing to form the bulk silicate Earth, leaving behind an atmosphere largely consisting of water vapor, nitrogen, and carbon dioxide, with smaller amounts of carbon monoxide, hydrogen, and sulfur compounds.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] The solution of carbon dioxide in water is thought to have made the seas slightly acidic, with a pH of about 5.5.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Condensation to form liquid oceans is theorised to have occurred as early as the Moon-forming impact.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] This scenario is supported by the dating of 4.404 Gya zircon crystals with high *δ*18O values from metamorphosed quartzite of Mount Narryer in Western Australia.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] The Hadean atmosphere has been characterized as a "gigantic, productive outdoor chemical laboratory," similar to volcanic gases today which still support some abiotic chemistry.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Despite the likely increased volcanism from early plate tectonics, the Earth may have been a predominantly water world between 4.4 and 4.3 Gya.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] It is debated whether crust was exposed above this ocean.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Immediately after the Moon-forming impact, Earth likely had little if any continental crust, a turbulent atmosphere, and a hydrosphere subject to intense ultraviolet light from a T Tauri stage Sun.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] It was also affected by cosmic radiation, and continued asteroid and comet impacts.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] The Late Heavy Bombardment hypothesis posits that a period of intense impact occurred at 4.1 to 3.8 Gya during the Hadean and early Archean eons.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Originally it was thought that the Late Heavy Bombardment was a single cataclysmic impact event occurring at 3.9 Gya; this would have had the potential to sterilize Earth by volatilizing liquid oceans and blocking sunlight needed for photosynthesis, delaying the earliest possible emergence of life.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] More recent research questioned the intensity of the Late Heavy Bombardment and its potential for sterilisation.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] If it was not one giant impact but a period of raised impact rate, it would have had much less destructive power.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] The 3.9 Gya date arose from dating of Apollo mission sample returns collected mostly near the Imbrium Basin, biasing the age of recorded impacts.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Impact modelling of the lunar surface reveals that rather than a cataclysmic event at 3.9 Gya, multiple small-scale, short-lived periods of bombardment likely occurred.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Terrestrial data backs this idea by showing multiple periods of ejecta in the rock record both before and after the 3.9 Gya marker, suggesting that the early Earth was subject to continuous impacts with less impact on extinction.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from late impacts and the then high levels of ultraviolet radiation from the sun.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] The available energy is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Based on evidence from the geologic record, life most likely emerged on Earth between 4.32 and 3.48 Gya.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] In 2017, the earliest physical evidence of life was reported to consist of microbialites in the Nuvvuagittuq Greenstone Belt of Northern Quebec, in banded iron formation rocks at least 3.77 and possibly as old as 4.32 Gya.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] The micro-organisms could have lived within hydrothermal vent precipitates, soon after the 4.4 Gya formation of oceans during the Hadean.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] The microbes resemble modern hydrothermal vent bacteria, supporting the view that abiogenesis began in such an environment.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Later research disputed this interpretation of the data, stating that the observations may be better explained by abiotic processes in silica-rich waters, "chemical gardens," circulating hydrothermal fluids, or volcanic ejecta.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Biogenic graphite has been found in 3.7 Gya metasedimentary rocks from southwestern Greenland and in microbial mat fossils from 3.49 Gya cherts in the Pilbara region of Western Australia.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Evidence of early life in rocks from Akilia Island, near the Isua supracrustal belt in southwestern Greenland, dating to 3.7 Gya, have shown biogenic carbon isotopes.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] In other parts of the Isua supracrustal belt, graphite inclusions trapped within garnet crystals are connected to the other elements of life: oxygen, nitrogen, and possibly phosphorus in the form of phosphate, providing further evidence for life 3.7 Gya.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] In the Pilbara region of Western Australia, compelling evidence of early life was found in pyrite-bearing sandstone in a fossilized beach, with rounded tubular cells that oxidized sulfur by photosynthesis in the absence of oxygen.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon isotope ratios on graphite inclusions from the Jack Hills zircons suggest that life could have existed on Earth from 4.1 Gya.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 study inferred LUCA's age as around 4.2 Gya (4.09–4.33 Gya) by analysing pre-LUCA gene duplicates, with calibration from fossil micro-organisms, much sooner after the origin of life than previously thought.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] The Pilbara region of Western Australia contains the Dresser Formation with rocks 3.48 Gya, including layered structures called stromatolites.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Their modern counterparts are created by photosynthetic micro-organisms including cyanobacteria.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] These lie within undeformed hydrothermal-sedimentary strata; their texture indicates a biogenic origin.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Parts of the Dresser formation preserve hot springs on land, but other regions seem to have been shallow seas.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] A molecular clock analysis suggests the LUCA emerged prior to 3.9 Gya.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] All chemical elements derive from stellar nucleosynthesis except for hydrogen and some helium and lithium.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Basic chemical ingredients of life – the carbon-hydrogen molecule (CH), the carbon-hydrogen positive ion (CH+) and the carbon ion (C+) – can be produced by ultraviolet light from stars.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Complex molecules, including organic molecules, form naturally both in space and on planets.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] An organic compound is a chemical whose molecules contain carbon.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon is abundant in the Sun, stars, comets, and in the atmospheres of most planets of the Solar System.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds are relatively common in space, formed by "factories of complex molecular synthesis" which occur in molecular clouds and circumstellar envelopes, and chemically evolve after reactions are initiated mostly by ionizing radiation.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Purine and pyrimidine nucleobases including guanine, adenine, cytosine, uracil, and thymine, as well as sugars, have been found in meteorites.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] These could have provided the materials for DNA and RNA to form on the early Earth.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] The amino acid glycine was found in material ejected from comet Wild 2; it had earlier been detected in meteorites.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Comets are encrusted with dark material, thought to be a tar-like organic substance formed from simple carbon compounds under ionizing radiation.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] A rain of material from comets could have brought such complex organic molecules to Earth.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] During the Late Heavy Bombardment, meteorites may have delivered up to five million tons of organic prebiotic elements to Earth per year.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Currently 40,000 tons of cosmic dust falls to Earth each year.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAH) are the most common and abundant polyatomic molecules in the observable universe, and are a major store of carbon.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] They seem to have formed shortly after the Big Bang, and are associated with new stars and exoplanets.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] They are a likely constituent of Earth's primordial sea.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs have been detected in nebulae, and in the interstellar medium, in comets, and in meteorites.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] A star, HH 46-IR, resembling the sun early in its life, is surrounded by a disk of material which contains molecules including cyanide compounds, hydrocarbons, and carbon monoxide.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs in the interstellar medium can be transformed through hydrogenation, oxygenation, and hydroxylation to more complex organic compounds used in living cells.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds introduced on Earth by interstellar dust particles can help to form complex molecules, thanks to their peculiar surface-catalytic activities.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA component uracil and related molecules, including xanthine, in the Murchison meteorite were likely formed extraterrestrially, as suggested by studies of 12C/13C isotopic ratios.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] NASA studies of meteorites suggest that all four DNA nucleobases (adenine, guanine and related organic molecules) have been formed in outer space.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] The cosmic dust permeating the universe contains complex organics ("amorphous organic solids with a mixed aromatic–aliphatic structure") that could be created rapidly by stars.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Glycolaldehyde, a sugar molecule and RNA precursor, has been detected in regions of space including around protostars and on meteorites.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] As early as the 1860s, experiments demonstrated that biologically relevant molecules can be produced from interaction of simple carbon sources with abundant inorganic catalysts.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] The spontaneous formation of complex polymers from abiotically generated monomers under the conditions posited by the "soup" theory is not straightforward.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Besides the necessary basic organic monomers, compounds that would have prohibited the formation of polymers were also formed in high concentration during the Miller–Urey experiment and Joan Oró experiments.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Biology uses essentially 20 amino acids for its coded protein enzymes, representing a very small subset of the structurally possible products.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Since life tends to use whatever is available, an explanation is needed for why the set used is so small.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide is attractive as a medium that potentially provided a source of amino acid derivatives from simple aldehyde and nitrile feedstocks.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Alexander Butlerov showed in 1861 that the formose reaction created sugars including tetroses, pentoses, and hexoses when formaldehyde is heated under basic conditions with divalent metal ions like calcium.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Breslow proposed that the reaction was autocatalytic in 1959.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Nucleobases, such as guanine and adenine, can be synthesized from simple carbon and nitrogen sources, such as hydrogen cyanide (HCN) and ammonia.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] On early Earth, HCN was likely supplied via photochemical production in a transient, highly reducing atmosphere after major impacts.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide, from the reaction of water and HCN, produces all four ribonucleotides when warmed with terrestrial minerals.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] HCN can contribute to chemical processes such as the synthesis of the amino acid glycine.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] DNA and RNA components including uracil, cytosine and thymine can be synthesized under outer space conditions, using starting chemicals such as pyrimidine from meteorites.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Pyrimidine may have formed in red giant stars, interstellar dust, or gas clouds, or on Earth via precursors such as cyanoacetylene following asteroid impacts.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] All four RNA-bases may be synthesized from formamide in high-energy density events like extraterrestrial impacts.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Several ribonucleotides for RNA formation have been synthesized in a laboratory environment which replicates prebiotic conditions via autocatalytic formose reaction.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Other pathways for synthesizing bases from inorganic materials have been reported.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Freezing temperatures assist the synthesis of purines, by concentrating key precursors such as HCN.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] However, while adenine and guanine require freezing conditions, cytosine and uracil may require boiling temperatures.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Seven amino acids and eleven types of nucleobases formed in ice when ammonia and cyanide were left in a freezer for 25 years.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] S-triazines (alternative nucleobases), pyrimidines including cytosine and uracil, and adenine can be synthesized by subjecting a urea solution to freeze-thaw cycles under a reductive atmosphere with spark discharges.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] These low-temperature reactions proceed rapidly due to eutectic freezing, which crowds impurities in microscopic pockets of liquid within the ice.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic peptide synthesis could have occurred by several routes.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Some center on high temperature/concentration conditions in which condensation becomes energetically favorable, while others use plausible prebiotic condensing agents.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Experimental evidence for the formation of peptides in uniquely concentrated environments is bolstered by work suggesting that wet-dry cycles and the presence of specific salts can greatly increase spontaneous condensation of glycine into poly-glycine chains.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Other work suggests that while mineral surfaces, such as those of pyrite, calcite, and rutile catalyze peptide condensation, they also catalyze their hydrolysis.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] The authors suggest that additional chemical activation or coupling would be necessary to produce peptides at sufficient concentrations.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Thus, mineral surface catalysis, while important, is not sufficient alone for peptide synthesis.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Many prebiotically plausible condensing/activating agents have been identified, including the following: cyanamide, dicyanamide, dicyandiamide, diaminomaleonitrile, urea, trimetaphosphate, NaCl, CuCl2, (Ni,Fe)S, CO, carbonyl sulfide (COS), carbon disulfide (CS2), SO2, and diammonium phosphate (DAP).
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 experiment used a sapphire substrate with a web of thin cracks under a heat flow, mimicking deep-ocean vents, to concentrate prebiotically-relevant building blocks from a dilute mixture by up to three orders of magnitude.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] This could help to create biopolymers such as peptides.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] A similar role has been suggested for clays, though this speculation has not been supported through experimental evidence.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] The prebiotic synthesis of peptides from simpler molecules such as CO, NH3 and C, skipping the step of amino acid formation, is also very efficient.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] The largest unanswered question in evolution is how simple protocells first arose and differed in reproductive contribution to the following generation, thus initiating evolution.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] The lipid world theory postulates that the first self-replicating object was lipid-like.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Phospholipids form lipid bilayers (as in cell membranes) in water while under agitation.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] These molecules were not present on early Earth, but other membrane-forming amphiphilic long-chain molecules were.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] These bodies may expand by insertion of additional lipids, and may spontaneously split into two offspring of similar size and composition.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Lipid bodies may have provided sheltering envelopes for information storage, allowing the evolution of information-storing polymers like RNA.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Only one or two types of vesicle-forming amphiphiles have been studied.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Such site/compound pairs are transmissible to the daughter vesicles, leading to the emergence of distinct lineages of vesicles, subject to natural selection.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] A protocell is a self-organized, self-ordered, spherical collection of lipids proposed as a stepping-stone to life, that is capable of evolving.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembled vesicles are essential components of primitive cells.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] The theory of classical irreversible thermodynamics treats self-assembly under a generalized chemical potential within the framework of dissipative systems.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] The second law of thermodynamics requires that overall entropy increases, yet life is distinguished by its great degree of organization.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Therefore, a boundary is needed to separate ordered life processes from chaotic non-living matter.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] A functional protocell, which must exhibit Darwinian evolution, has not yet been achieved in a laboratory setting.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Szostak suggest that elementary protocells can give rise to primitive forms of differential reproduction, competition, and energy storage.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Competition for membrane molecules would favor stabilized membranes, suggesting a selective advantage for cross-linked fatty acids and even modern phospholipids.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Such micro-encapsulation would allow for metabolism within the membrane and the exchange of small molecules, while retaining large biomolecules inside.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Such a membrane is needed for a cell to create its own electrochemical gradient.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Vesicles can undergo an evolutionary process under pressure cycling conditions.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Simulating the systemic environment in tectonic fault zones within the Earth's crust, pressure cycling forms vesicles periodically, as well as random peptide chains which are selected for ability to integrate into the vesicle membrane.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Further selection of vesicles for stability could lead to functional peptide structures, increasing vesicle survival rate.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Life requires a loss of entropy, or disorder, as molecules organize themselves into living matter.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] At the same time, the emergence of life is associated with the formation of structures beyond a certain threshold of complexity.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Multiple sources of energy were available for chemical reactions on the early Earth.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Heat from geothermal processes is a standard energy source for chemistry.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Other examples include sunlight, lightning, atmospheric entries of micro-meteorites, and implosion of bubbles in sea and ocean waves.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] This has been confirmed by experiments and simulations.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Unfavorable reactions can be driven by highly favorable ones, as in the case of iron-sulfur chemistry.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] For example, this was probably important for carbon fixation.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon fixation by reaction of CO2 with H2S via iron-sulfur chemistry is favorable, and occurs at neutral pH and 100 °C.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Iron-sulfur surfaces, which are abundant near hydrothermal vents, can drive the production of small amounts of amino acids and other biomolecules.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] In 1961, Peter Mitchell proposed chemiosmosis as a cell's primary system of energy conversion.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism, now ubiquitous in living cells, powers energy conversion in micro-organisms and in the mitochondria of eukaryotes, making it a likely candidate for early life.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Mitochondria produce adenosine triphosphate (ATP), the energy currency of the cell used to drive cellular processes such as chemical syntheses.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism of ATP synthesis involves a closed membrane in which the ATP synthase enzyme is embedded.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] The energy required to release strongly bound ATP has its origin in protons that move across the membrane.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] In modern cells, those proton movements are caused by the pumping of ions across the membrane, maintaining an electrochemical gradient.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] However, as yet, the hypothesis is untested.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA world hypothesis describes an early Earth with self-replicating and catalytic RNA but no DNA or proteins.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] It was proposed in 1962 by Alexander Rich; the term was coined by Walter Gilbert in 1986.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Many researchers concur that an RNA world must have preceded modern DNA-based life.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] However, it may not have been the first to exist.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] There may have been over 30 chemical events between pre-RNA world to near-LUCA, just involving RNA.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] RNA is central to the translation process.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Small RNAs can catalyze all the chemical groups and information transfers required for life.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] RNA both expresses and maintains genetic information in modern organisms; its components are easily synthesized under early Earth conditions.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] The structure of the ribosome has been called the "smoking gun", with a central core of RNA and no amino acid side chains within 18 Å of the active site that catalyzes peptide bond formation.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] RNA replicase can both code and catalyse further RNA replication, i.e. it is autocatalytic.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Some catalytic RNAs can link smaller RNA sequences together, enabling self-replication.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Natural selection would then favor the proliferation of such autocatalytic sets.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembly of RNA may occur spontaneously in hydrothermal vents.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] A preliminary form of tRNA could have assembled into a replicator molecule.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] When this began to replicate, it may have had all three mechanisms of Darwinian selection: heritability, variation, and differential reproduction.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Its fitness would have depended on its ability to adapt, determined by its nucleotide sequence, and resource availability.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Starting with the work of Carl Woese from 1977, genomics studies have placed the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) of all modern life-forms between Bacteria and a clade formed by Archaea and Eukaryota in the phylogenetic tree of life.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] A minority of studies have placed the LUCA in Bacteria, proposing that Archaea and Eukaryota are evolutionarily derived from within Eubacteria; Thomas Cavalier-Smith suggested in 2006 that the phenotypically diverse bacterial phylum Chloroflexota contained the LUCA.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] In 2016, a set of 355 genes likely present in the LUCA was identified.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] A total of 6.1 million prokaryotic genes from Bacteria and Archaea were sequenced, identifying 355 protein clusters from among 286,514 protein clusters that were probably common to the LUCA.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] The results suggest that the LUCA was anaerobic with a Wood–Ljungdahl (reductive Acetyl-CoA) pathway, nitrogen- and carbon-fixing, thermophilic.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Its cofactors suggest dependence upon an environment rich in hydrogen, carbon dioxide, iron, and transition metals.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Its genetic material was probably DNA, requiring the 4-nucleotide genetic code, messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins such as enzymes.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] LUCA likely inhabited an anaerobic hydrothermal vent setting in a geochemically active environment.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] It was evidently already a complex organism, and must have had precursors; it was not the first living thing.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] The physiology of LUCA has been in dispute.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Previous research identified 60 proteins common to all life.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p01] Metabolic reactions inferred in LUCA are the incomplete reverse Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, the pentose phosphate pathway, glycolysis, reductive amination, and transamination.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] A variety of geologic and environmental settings have been proposed for an origin of life.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] These theories are often in competition with one another as there are many views of prebiotic compound availability, geophysical setting, and early life characteristics.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] The first organism on Earth likely differed from LUCA.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Between the first appearance of life and where all modern phylogenies began branching, an unknown amount of time passed, with unknown gene transfers, extinctions, and adaptation to environmental niches.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Modern phylogenies provide more genetic evidence about LUCA than about its precursors.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Early micro-fossils may have come from a hot world of gases such as methane, ammonia, carbon dioxide, and hydrogen sulfide, toxic to much current life.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Analysis of the tree of life places thermophilic and hyperthermophilic bacteria and archaea closest to the root, suggesting that life may have evolved in a hot environment.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] The deep sea or alkaline hydrothermal vent theory posits that life began at submarine hydrothermal vents.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] William Martin and Michael Russell have suggested that this could have been in metal-sulphide-walled compartments acting as precursors for cell walls.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] These form where hydrogen-rich fluids emerge from below the sea floor, as a result of serpentinization of ultra-mafic olivine with seawater and a pH interface with carbon dioxide-rich ocean water.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] The vents form a sustained chemical energy source derived from redox reactions, in which electron donors (molecular hydrogen) react with electron acceptors (carbon dioxide); see iron–sulfur world theory.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Russell demonstrated that alkaline vents create an abiogenic proton motive force chemiosmotic gradient, ideal for abiogenesis.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Their microscopic compartments "provide a natural means of concentrating organic molecules," composed of iron-sulfur minerals such as mackinawite, endowed these mineral cells with the catalytic properties envisaged by Günter Wächtershäuser.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Electrostatic force caused by electrical potential gradient—cations like protons H+ diffuse down the electrical potential, anions in the opposite direction.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] These two gradients together can be expressed as an electrochemical gradient, providing energy for abiogenic synthesis.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] The proton motive force measures the potential energy stored as proton and voltage gradients across a membrane (differences in proton concentration and electrical potential).
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] In 2016, Martin suggested that the LUCA "may have depended heavily on the geothermal energy of the vent to survive".
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] That same year, RNA was produced in synthetic alkaline hydrothermal chimneys simulating deep-sea vents.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Researchers were able to generate RNA oligomers of up to 4 units in length.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] This RNA was synthesized using activated ribonucleotides.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Additionally, these RNA oligomers could only be synthesized under certain conditions.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Pores at deep sea hydrothermal vents are suggested to have been occupied by membrane-bound compartments which promoted biochemical reactions.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Metabolic intermediates in the Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, amino acid bio-synthetic pathways, glycolysis, the pentose phosphate pathway, and including sugars like ribose, and lipid precursors can occur non-enzymatically at conditions relevant to deep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] If the deep marine hydrothermal setting was the site, then life could have arisen as early as 4.0–4.2 Gya.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from impacts and the then high levels of solar ultraviolet radiation.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] The available energy in hydrothermal vents is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Hyperthermophily could have been a result of convergent evolution in bacteria and archaea; a mesophilic environment has been called more likely.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Production of prebiotic organic compounds at hydrothermal vents is estimated to be 108 kg/yr.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Key prebiotic compounds, such as methane are in far lower concentrations at vents than in a Miller-Urey Experiment environment.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Some organic compounds are now understood to have been formed by other geological processes and inherited by vents.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Methane, for example, more likely comes from leached fluid inclusions formed deeper in oceanic crust from magmatic carbon.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Vents do not concentrate prebiotic materials, due to strong dilution by seawater.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] This open system cycles compounds through vent minerals, leaving little residence time to accumulate.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] All modern cells rely on phosphates for nucleotide backbone and potassium for protein formation, making it likely that the first life forms shared these functions.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] These elements were not available in high quantities in the Archaean oceans.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] However, phosphate can be concentrated in lakes, as in the modern Last Chance Lake.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Submarine hydrothermal vents are not conducive to condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] An older argument was that key polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation, which supposedly would not happen in saltwater.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] However, while salinity inhibits vesicle formation from low-diversity mixtures of fatty acids, vesicle formation from a broader, more realistic mix of fatty-acid and 1-alkanol species is more resilient.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] No studies have been able to experimentally demonstrate synthesis of sugars, amino acids, nucleases, nucleosides, nucleotides, or membrane-forming fatty acids under plausible vent conditions.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Surface bodies of water provide environments that dry out and rewet.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Wet-dry cycles concentrate prebiotic compounds and enable condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, lakes and ponds receive detrital input from weathering of continental apatite-containing rocks, the most common source of phosphates.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] The amount of exposed continental crust in the Hadean is unknown, but models of early ocean depths and rates of ocean island and continental crust growth make it plausible that there was exposed land.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Another line of evidence for a surface start to life is the requirement for Ultraviolet radiation (UV) for organism function.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] UV is necessary for the formation of the U+C nucleotide base pair by partial hydrolysis and nucleobase loss.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Simultaneously, UV can be harmful and sterilising to life, especially for simple early lifeforms with little ability to repair radiation damage.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Radiation levels from a young Sun were likely greater, and, with no ozone layer, harmful shortwave UV rays would reach the surface of Earth.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] For life to begin, a shielded environment with influx from UV-exposed sources is necessary to both benefit and protect from UV.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Shielding under ice, liquid water, mineral surfaces (e.g. clay) or regolith is possible in a range of surface water settings.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Most branching phylogenies are thermophilic or hyperthermophilic, making it possible that LUCA and preceding lifeforms were similarly thermophilic.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs are formed from the heating of groundwater by geothermal activity.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] This intersection allows for influxes of material from deep penetrating waters and from surface runoff that transports eroded continental sediments.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Interconnected groundwater systems create a mechanism for distribution of life to wider area.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Mulkidjanian and co-authors argue that marine environments did not provide the ionic balance and composition universally found in cells, or the ions required by essential proteins and ribozymes, especially with respect to high K+/Na+ ratio, Mn2+, Zn2+ and phosphate concentrations.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] They argue that the only environments that do this are hot springs similar to ones at Kamchatka.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] The hypothesized pre-biotic environments are similar to hydrothermal vents, with additional components that help explain peculiarities of the LUCA.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] A phylogenomic and geochemical analysis of proteins plausibly traced to the LUCA shows that the ionic composition of its intracellular fluid is identical to that of hot springs.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] The LUCA likely was dependent upon synthesized organic matter for its growth.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments show that RNA-like polymers can be synthesized in wet-dry cycling and UV light exposure.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] These polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Potential sources of organics at hot springs might have been transported by interplanetary dust particles, extraterrestrial projectiles, or atmospheric or geochemical synthesis.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs could have been abundant in volcanic landmasses during the Hadean.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] A mesophilic start in surface bodies of waters hypothesis has evolved from Darwin's concept of a 'warm little pond' and the Oparin-Haldane hypothesis.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Freshwater bodies under temperate climates can accumulate prebiotic materials while providing suitable environmental conditions conducive to simple life forms.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Atmospheric reconstructions from geochemical proxies and models suggest that sufficient greenhouse gases were present to maintain surface temperatures between 0–40 °C.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] If so, the temperature was suitable for life to begin.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Evidence for mesophily from biomolecular studies includes Galtier's G+C nucleotide thermometer.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] G+C are more abundant in thermophiles due to the added stability of an additional hydrogen bond not present between A+T nucleotides. rRNA sequencing of modern lifeforms shows that LUCA's reconstructed G+C content was likely representative of moderate temperatures.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] The diversity of thermophiles today could be a product of convergent evolution and horizontal gene transfer rather than an inherited trait from LUCA.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] The reverse gyrase topoisomerase is found exclusively in thermophiles and hyperthermophiles, as it allows for coiling of DNA.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] This enzyme requires the complex molecule ATP to function.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] If an origin of life is hypothesised to involve a simple organism that had not yet evolved a membrane, let alone ATP, this would make the existence of reverse gyrase improbable.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, phylogenetic studies show that reverse gyrase originated in archaea, and transferred to bacteria by horizontal gene transfer, implying it was not present in the LUCA.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Cold-start theories presuppose large ice-covered regions.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Stellar evolution models predict that the Sun's luminosity was ≈25% weaker than it is today.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Fuelner states that although this significant decrease in solar energy would have formed an icy planet, there is strong evidence for the presence of liquid water, possibly driven by a greenhouse effect.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] This would mean an early Earth with both liquid oceans and icy poles.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Ice melts that form from ice sheets or glacier melts create freshwater pools, another niche capable of wet-dry cycles.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] While surface pools would be exposed to intense UV radiation, bodies of water within and under ice would be shielded, while remaining connected to exposed areas through ice cracks.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Impact melting would allow freshwater and meteoritic input, creating prebiotic components.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Near-seawater levels of sodium chloride destabilize fatty acid membrane self-assembly, making freshwater settings appealing for early membranous life.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Icy environments would trade the faster reaction rates that occur in warm environments for increased stability and accumulation of larger polymers.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments simulating Europa-like conditions of ≈20 °C have synthesised amino acids and adenine, showing that Miller-Urey type syntheses can occur at low temperatures.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] In an RNA world, the ribozyme would have had even more functions than in a later DNA-RNA-protein-world.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] For RNA to function, it must be able to fold, a process hindered by temperatures above 30 °C.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] While RNA folding in psychrophilic organisms is slower, so is hydrolysis, so folding is more successful.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Shorter nucleotides would not suffer from higher temperatures.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] The continental crust, with tectonic fault zones could present a stable and well-protected environment for long-term prebiotic evolution.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Inside these systems of cracks and cavities, water and carbon dioxide present the bulk solvents.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Their phase state could vary between liquid, gaseous and supercritical, depending on pressure and temperature.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] When forming two separate phases, the system provides optimal conditions for phase transfer reactions.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Concurrently, the contents of the tectonic fault zones are supplied with inorganic educts (e.g. carbon monoxide, hydrogen, ammonia, hydrogen cyanide, nitrogen, and phosphate) and simple organic molecules (e.g. amino acids, long-chain amines, fatty acids, long-chain aldehydes).
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Part of the tectonic fault zones is at a depth of around 1000 m.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] For carbon dioxide, it provides temperature and pressure conditions near the phase transition point between the supercritical and the gaseous state.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] This allows lipophilic organic molecules that dissolve well in supercritical CO2 to accumulate, leading to local precipitation.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Periodic pressure variations such as caused by geysers or tidal influences result in periodic phase transitions, keeping the local reaction environment in a constant non-equilibrium state.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] In presence of amphiphilic compounds (such as the long chain amines and fatty acids), subsequent generations of vesicles are formed that are selected for their stability.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Homochirality is the uniformity of materials composed of chiral (non-mirror-symmetric) units.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Living organisms use molecules with the same chirality: with almost no exceptions, amino acids are left-handed while nucleotides and sugars are right-handed.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Chiral molecules can be synthesized, but in the absence of a chiral source or a chiral catalyst, they are formed in a 50/50 (racemic) mixture of both forms.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Non-racemic mixtures can arise from racemic materials by asymmetric physical laws such as the electroweak interaction, or in asymmetric environments, such as those in which molecules are exposed to circularly polarized light of a given handedness.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] It has been hypothesized that the solar nebula was such an environment, exposed to circularly-polarized radiation from an external source before or during the epoch of planet formation.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] This proposal is consistent with the finding that some amino acids delivered to Earth in meteorites exhibit a chiral asymmetry of the same sign as terrestrial life.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] Once established, a chirality imbalance may influence subsequent chemical evolution.
[src:ammonia/abiogenesis-p02] A small bias in the population can be amplified by asymmetric autocatalysis, as in the Soai reaction, where a chiral molecule catalyzes its own production.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] An **absorption refrigerator** is a refrigerator that uses a heat source to provide the energy needed to drive the cooling process.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] Solar energy, burning oil, waste heat from factories, and district heating systems are examples of heat sources that can be used.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] An absorption refrigerator uses two coolants, the first coolant performing evaporative cooling before being absorbed into the second coolant.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] Heat is then needed to reset the two coolants to their initial states.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption refrigerators are commonly used in recreational vehicles (RVs), campers, and caravans because the heat required to power them can be provided by either a propane fuel burner, a low-voltage DC electric heater (from a battery or vehicle electrical system) or a mains-powered electric heater.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption refrigerators can also be used to air-condition buildings using the waste heat from a gas turbine or water heater in the building.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] Using waste heat from a gas turbine makes the turbine very efficient because it first produces electricity, then hot water, and finally, air-conditioning—trigeneration.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] Unlike more common vapor-compression refrigeration systems, an absorption refrigerator has no moving parts and operates almost silently.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption refrigerators are an alternative to compressor refrigerators where electricity is unreliable, costly, or unavailable; also the silent action of the absorption refrigerator is an advantage where noise from the compressor is problematic; or where surplus heat is available.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] In 1748 in Glasgow, William Cullen invented the basis for modern refrigeration, although he is not credited with a usable application.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] More on history of refrigeration can be found in the paragraph Refrigeration Research on page Refrigeration.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption refrigeration uses the same principle as adsorption refrigeration, which was invented by Michael Faraday in 1821.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] Instead of using a solid adsorber, an absorber in an absorption system absorbs the refrigerant vapour into a liquid.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption cooling was invented by the French scientist Ferdinand Carré in 1858.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] The original design used water and sulphuric acid.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] The principle was enhanced with a three-fluid configuration in 1922 by Baltzar von Platen and Carl Munters, two students at the Royal Institute of Technology in Stockholm.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] This "Platen-Munters" design can operate without a pump.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] Also in the 1960s, absorption refrigeration saw a renaissance due to the substantial demand for refrigerators for caravans.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] AB Electrolux later established a subsidiary in the United States, named Dometic Sales Corporation.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] The company marketed refrigerators for recreational vehicles (RVs) under the *Dometic* brand.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] In 2001, Electrolux sold most of its leisure products line to the venture-capital company EQT which created *Dometic* as a stand-alone company.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] Dometic still sold absorption fridges as of July 2025.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] In 1926, Albert Einstein and his former student Leó Szilárd proposed an alternative design known as the Einstein refrigerator.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] At the 2007 TED Conference, Adam Grosser presented his research of an "intermittent absorption" vaccine refrigeration unit for use in third world countries.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] The refrigerator is a small unit placed over a campfire, that can later be used to cool 15 litres (3.3 imp gal; 4.0 US gal) of water to just above freezing for 24 hours in a 30 °C (86 °F) environment.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] The concept was similar to an early refrigeration device known as an Icyball.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] Common absorption refrigerators use a refrigerant with a very low boiling point (less than −18 °C (0 °F)) just like compressor refrigerators.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] Compression refrigerators typically use an HCFC or HFC, while absorption refrigerators typically use ammonia or water and need at least a second fluid able to absorb the coolant, the *absorbent*, respectively water (for ammonia) or brine (for water).
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] Both types use evaporative cooling: when the refrigerant evaporates (boils), it takes some heat away with it, providing the cooling effect.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] The main difference between the two systems is the way the refrigerant is changed from a gas back into a liquid so that the cycle can repeat.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] An absorption refrigerator changes the gas back into a liquid using a method that needs only heat, and has no moving parts other than the fluids.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] The system thus silently provides for the mechanical circulation of the liquid without a usual pump.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] A third fluid, gaseous, is usually added to avoid pressure concerns when condensation occurs (see below).
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] In comparison, a compressor based heat pump works by pumping refrigerant gas from an evaporator to a condenser.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] This reduces the pressure and boiling temperature in the evaporator and increases the pressure and condensing temperature in the condenser.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] Energy from an electric motor or internal combustion engine is required to operate the compressor pump.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] Compressing the refrigerant uses this energy to do work on the gas, increasing its temperature.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] The warm, high pressure gas then enters the condenser where it undergoes a phase change to a liquid and releases heat to the condenser's surroundings.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] Warm liquid refrigerant moves from the high pressure condenser to the low pressure evaporator via an expansion valve, also known as a throttling valve or a Joule-Thomson valve.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] The expansion valve partially vaporizes the refrigerant cooling it via evaporative cooling, and the resulting vapor is cooled via expansive cooling.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] This is a combination of Joule-Thomson cooling and work done by the expanding gas, both at the expense of the internal energy of the gas.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] The cold, low pressure liquid refrigerant will now absorb heat from the evaporator's surroundings and vaporize.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] The resulting gas enters the compressor, and the cycle begins again.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] A simple absorption refrigeration system common in large commercial plants uses a solution of lithium bromide or lithium chloride salt and water.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] Water under low pressure is evaporated from the coils that are to be chilled.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] The water is absorbed by a lithium bromide/water solution.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] The system drives the water out of the lithium bromide solution with heat.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] Another variant uses air, water, and a salt water solution.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] The intake of warm, moist air is passed through a sprayed solution of salt water.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] The spray lowers the humidity but does not significantly change the temperature.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] The less humid, warm air is then passed through an evaporative cooler, consisting of a spray of fresh water, which cools and re-humidifies the air.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] Humidity is removed from the cooled air with another spray of salt solution, providing the outlet of cool, dry air.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] The salt solution is regenerated by heating it under low pressure, causing water to evaporate.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] The water evaporated from the salt solution is re-condensed, and rerouted back to the evaporative cooler.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] A single-pressure absorption refrigerator takes advantage of the fact that a liquid's evaporation rate depends upon the *partial* pressure of the vapor above the liquid and goes up with lower partial pressure.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] The refrigerator uses three substances: ammonia, hydrogen gas, and water.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] The cycle is closed, with all hydrogen, water and ammonia collected and endlessly reused.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] The cooling cycle starts with liquid ammonia at room temperature entering the evaporator.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] The volume of the evaporator is greater than the volume of the liquid, with the excess space occupied by a mixture of gaseous ammonia and hydrogen.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] The presence of hydrogen lowers the partial pressure of the ammonia gas, thus lowering the evaporation point of the liquid below the temperature of the refrigerator's interior.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] Ammonia evaporates, taking a small amount of heat from the liquid and lowering the liquid's temperature.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] It continues to evaporate, while the large enthalpy of vaporization (heat) flows from the warmer refrigerator interior to the cooler liquid ammonia and then to more ammonia gas.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] In the next two steps, the ammonia gas is separated from the hydrogen so it can be reused.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] The next step separates the ammonia and water.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] The ammonia/water solution flows to the generator (boiler), where heat is applied to boil off the ammonia, leaving most of the water (which has a higher boiling point) behind.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] Some water vapor and bubbles remain mixed with the ammonia; this water is removed in the final separation step, by passing it through the separator, an uphill series of twisted pipes with minor obstacles to pop the bubbles, allowing the water vapor to condense and drain back to the generator.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] The pure ammonia gas then enters the condenser.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] In this heat exchanger, the hot ammonia gas transfers its heat to the outside air, which is below the boiling point of the full-pressure ammonia, and therefore condenses.
[src:ammonia/absorption-refrigerator] The condensed (liquid) ammonia flows down to be mixed with the hydrogen gas released from the absorption step, repeating the cycle.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] The International Agency for Research on Cancer (IARC) has listed acetaldehyde as a Group 1 carcinogen.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is "one of the most frequently found air toxins with cancer risk greater than one in a million".
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] In 1835, Liebig named it "aldehyde", and in the middle of the century the name was altered to "acetaldehyde".
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] In 2013, global production was about 438,000 tonnes.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Before 1962, ethanol and acetylene were the major sources of acetaldehyde.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Since then, ethylene is the dominant feedstock.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] In the 1970s, the world capacity of the Wacker-Hoechst direct oxidation process exceeded two million tonnes annually.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Smaller quantities can be prepared by the partial oxidation of ethanol in an exothermic reaction.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] This process typically is conducted over a silver catalyst at about 500–650 °C (950–1,200 °F).
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] This method is one of the oldest routes for the industrial preparation of acetaldehyde.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Prior to the Wacker process and the availability of cheap ethylene, acetaldehyde was produced by the hydration of acetylene.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] The mechanism involves the intermediacy of vinyl alcohol, which tautomerizes to acetaldehyde.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] The reaction is conducted at 90–95 °C (194–203 °F), and the acetaldehyde formed is separated from water and mercury and cooled to 25–30 °C (77–86 °F).
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] In the wet oxidation process, iron(III) sulfate is used to reoxidize the mercury back to the mercury(II) salt.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] The resulting iron(II) sulfate is oxidized in a separate reactor with nitric acid.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] The enzyme Acetylene hydratase discovered in the strictly anaerobic bacterium *Pelobacter acetylenicus* can catalyze an analogous reaction without involving any compounds of mercury.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] However, it has thus far not been brought to any large-scale or commercial use.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] In this endothermic process, ethanol vapor is passed at 260–290 °C over a copper-based catalyst.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] The process was once attractive because of the value of the hydrogen coproduct, but in modern times is not economically viable.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] The hydroformylation of methanol with catalysts like cobalt, nickel, or iron salts also produces acetaldehyde, although this process is of no industrial importance.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Similarly noncompetitive, acetaldehyde arises from synthesis gas with modest selectivity.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] The equilibrium constant is 6×10−7 at room temperature, thus that the relative amount of the enol form in a sample of acetaldehyde is very small.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] At room temperature, acetaldehyde (CH3CH=O) is more stable than vinyl alcohol (CH2=CHOH) by 42.7 kJ/mol: Overall the keto-enol tautomerization occurs slowly but is catalyzed by acids.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Photo-induced keto-enol tautomerization is viable under atmospheric or stratospheric conditions.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] This photo-tautomerization is relevant to the Earth's atmosphere, because vinyl alcohol is thought to be a precursor to carboxylic acids in the atmosphere.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is a common electrophile in organic synthesis.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] In addition reactions acetaldehyde is prochiral.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] It is used primarily as a source of the "CH3C+H(OH)" synthon in aldol reactions and related condensation reactions.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Grignard reagents and organolithium compounds react with MeCHO to give hydroxyethyl derivatives.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] In one of the more spectacular addition reactions, formaldehyde in the presence of calcium hydroxide adds to MeCHO to give pentaerythritol, C(CH2OH)4 and formate.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] In a Strecker reaction, acetaldehyde condenses with cyanide and ammonia to give, after hydrolysis, the amino acid alanine.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde can condense with amines to yield imines; for example, with cyclohexylamine to give *N*-ethylidenecyclohexylamine.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] These imines can be used to direct subsequent reactions like an aldol condensation.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] It is also a building block in the synthesis of heterocyclic compounds.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] In one example, it converts, upon treatment with ammonia, to 5-ethyl-2-methylpyridine ("aldehyde-collidine").
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Three molecules of acetaldehyde condense to form "paraldehyde", a cyclic trimer containing C-O single bonds.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Similarly condensation of four molecules of acetaldehyde give the cyclic molecule metaldehyde.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Paraldehyde can be produced in good yields, using a sulfuric acid catalyst.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Metaldehyde is only obtained in a few percent yield and with cooling, often using HBr rather than H2SO4 as the catalyst.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] At −40 °C (−40 °F) in the presence of acid catalysts, polyacetaldehyde is produced.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] There are two stereomers of paraldehyde and four of metaldehyde.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] The German chemist Valentin Hermann Weidenbusch (1821–1893) synthesized paraldehyde in 1848 by treating acetaldehyde with acid (either sulfuric or nitric acid) and cooling to 0 °C (32 °F).
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] He found it quite remarkable that when paraldehyde was *heated* with a trace of the same acid, the reaction went the other way, recreating acetaldehyde.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Although vinyl alcohol is a tautomeric form of acetaldehyde (§ Tautomerization to vinyl alcohol), polyvinyl alcohol cannot be produced from acetaldehyde.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde forms a stable acetal upon reaction with ethanol under conditions that favor dehydration.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] The product, CH3CH(OCH2CH3)2, is formally named 1,1-diethoxyethane but is commonly referred to as "acetal".
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] This can cause confusion as "acetal" is more commonly used to describe compounds with the functional groups RCH(OR')2 or RR'C(OR'')2 rather than referring to this specific compound — in fact, 1,1-diethoxyethane is also described as the diethyl acetal of acetaldehyde.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is a precursor to vinylphosphonic acid, which is used to make adhesives and ion conductive membranes.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] In the liver, the enzyme alcohol dehydrogenase oxidizes ethanol into acetaldehyde, which is then further oxidized into harmless acetic acid by acetaldehyde dehydrogenase.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] These two oxidation reactions are coupled with the reduction of NAD+ to NADH.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] In the brain, the enzyme catalase is primarily responsible for oxidizing ethanol to acetaldehyde, and alcohol dehydrogenase plays a minor role.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] The last steps of alcoholic fermentation in bacteria, plants, and yeast involve the conversion of pyruvate into acetaldehyde and carbon dioxide by the enzyme pyruvate decarboxylase, followed by the conversion of acetaldehyde into ethanol.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] The latter reaction is again catalyzed by an alcohol dehydrogenase, now operating in the opposite direction.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Many East Asian people have an ALDH2 mutation which makes them significantly less efficient at oxidizing acetaldehyde.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] On consuming alcohol, their bodies tend to accumulate excessive amounts of acetaldehyde, causing the so-called alcohol flush reaction.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] They develop a characteristic flush on the face and body, along with "nausea, headache and general physical discomfort".
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Ingestion of the drug disulfiram, which inhibits ALDH2, leads to a similar reaction .
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Traditionally, acetaldehyde was mainly used as a precursor to acetic acid.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] This application has declined because acetic acid is produced more efficiently from methanol by the Monsanto and Cativa processes.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is an important precursor to pyridine derivatives, pentaerythritol, and crotonaldehyde.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Urea and acetaldehyde combine to give a useful resin.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Acetic anhydride reacts with acetaldehyde to give ethylidene diacetate, a precursor to vinyl acetate, which is used to produce polyvinyl acetate.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] The global market for acetaldehyde is declining.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Demand has been impacted by changes in the production of plasticizer alcohols, which has shifted because *n*-butyraldehyde is less often produced from acetaldehyde, instead being generated by hydroformylation of propylene.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Likewise, acetic acid, once produced from acetaldehyde, is made predominantly by the lower-cost methanol carbonylation process.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] The impact on demand has led to increase in prices and thus slowdown in the market.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] China is the largest consumer of acetaldehyde in the world, accounting for almost half of global consumption in 2012.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Major use has been the production of acetic acid.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Other uses such as pyridines and pentaerythritol are expected to grow faster than acetic acid, but the volumes are not large enough to offset the decline in acetic acid.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] As a consequence, overall acetaldehyde consumption in China may grow slightly at 1.6% per year through 2018.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Western Europe is the second-largest consumer of acetaldehyde worldwide, accounting for 20% of world consumption in 2012.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] As with China, the Western European acetaldehyde market is expected to increase only very slightly at 1% per year during 2012–2018.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] However, Japan could emerge as a potential consumer for acetaldehyde in the next five years due to newfound use in commercial production of butadiene.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] The supply of butadiene has been volatile in Japan and the rest of Asia.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] This should provide the much needed boost to the flat market, as of 2013.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] The threshold limit value is 25 ppm (STEL/ceiling value) and the MAK (Maximum Workplace Concentration) is 50 ppm.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] At 50 ppm acetaldehyde, no irritation or local tissue damage in the nasal mucosa is observed.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] When taken up by the organism, acetaldehyde is metabolized rapidly in the liver to acetic acid.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Only a small proportion is exhaled unchanged.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] After intravenous injection, the half-life in the blood is approximately 90 seconds.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Many serious cases of acute intoxication have been recorded.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde naturally breaks down in the human body.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is an irritant of the skin, eyes, mucous membranes, throat, and respiratory tract.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] This occurs at concentrations as low as 1000 ppm.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Symptoms of exposure to this compound include nausea, vomiting, and headache.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] These symptoms may not happen immediately.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] The perception threshold for acetaldehyde in air is in the range between 0.07 and 0.25 ppm.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] At such concentrations, the fruity odor of acetaldehyde is apparent.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Conjunctival irritations have been observed after a 15-minute exposure to concentrations of 25 and 50 ppm, but transient conjunctivitis and irritation of the respiratory tract have been reported after exposure to 200 ppm acetaldehyde for 15 minutes.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] In addition, acetaldehyde is damaging to DNA and causes abnormal muscle development as it binds to proteins.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde induces DNA interstrand crosslinks, a form of DNA damage.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] These can be repaired by either of two replication-coupled DNA repair pathways.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] The first is referred to as the FA pathway, because it employs gene products defective in Fanconi's anemia patients.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] This repair pathway results in increased mutation frequency and altered mutational spectrum.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] The second repair pathway requires replication fork convergence, breakage of the acetaldehyde crosslink, translesion synthesis by a Y-family DNA polymerase and homologous recombination.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] People with a genetic deficiency for the enzyme responsible for the conversion of acetaldehyde into acetic acid may have a greater risk of Alzheimer's disease.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] A study of 818 heavy drinkers found that those exposed to more acetaldehyde than normal through a genetic variant of the gene encoding for ADH1C, ADH1C*1, are at greater risk of developing cancers of the upper gastrointestinal tract and liver.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] The drug disulfiram (Antabuse) inhibits acetaldehyde dehydrogenase, an enzyme that oxidizes the compound into acetic acid.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Metabolism of ethanol forms acetaldehyde before acetaldehyde dehydrogenase forms acetic acid, but with the enzyme inhibited, acetaldehyde accumulates.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] If one consumes ethanol while taking disulfiram, the hangover effect of ethanol is felt more rapidly and intensely (disulfiram-alcohol reaction).
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] As such, disulfiram is sometimes used as a deterrent for alcoholics wishing to stay sober.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is a potential contaminant in workplace, indoors, and ambient environments.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Moreover, the majority of humans spend more than 90% of their time in indoor environments, increasing any exposure and the risk to human health.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] In a study in France, the mean indoor concentration of acetaldehydes measured in 16 homes was approximately seven times higher than the outside acetaldehyde concentration.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] The living room had a mean of 18.1±17.5 μg m−3 and the bedroom was 18.2±16.9 μg m−3, whereas the outdoor air had a mean concentration of 2.3±2.6 μg m−3.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] It has been concluded that volatile organic compounds (VOC) such as benzene, formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, toluene, and xylenes have to be considered priority pollutants with respect to their health effects.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] It has been pointed that in renovated or completely new buildings, the VOCs concentration levels are often several orders of magnitude higher.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] The main sources of acetaldehydes in homes include building materials, laminate, PVC flooring, varnished wood flooring, and varnished cork/pine flooring (found in the varnish, not the wood).
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] It is also found in plastics, oil-based and water-based paints, in composite wood ceilings, particle-board, plywood, treated pine wood, and laminated chipboard furniture.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] The use of acetaldehyde is widespread in different industries, and it may be released into waste water or the air during production, use, transportation and storage.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Sources of acetaldehyde include fuel combustion emissions from stationary internal combustion engines and power plants that burn fossil fuels, wood, or trash, oil and gas extraction, refineries, cement kilns, lumber and wood mills and paper mills.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is also present in automobile and diesel exhaust.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] As a result, acetaldehyde is "one of the most frequently found air toxics with cancer risk greater than one in a million".
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Natural tobacco polysaccharides, including cellulose, have been shown to be the primary precursors making acetaldehyde a significant constituent of tobacco smoke.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] It has been demonstrated to have a synergistic effect with nicotine in rodent studies of addiction.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is also the most abundant carcinogen in tobacco smoke; it is dissolved into the saliva while smoking.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde has been found in cannabis smoke.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] This finding emerged through the use of new chemical techniques that demonstrated the acetaldehyde present was causing DNA damage in laboratory settings.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Many microbes produce acetaldehyde from ethanol, but they have a lower capacity to eliminate the acetaldehyde, which can lead to the accumulation of acetaldehyde in saliva, stomach acid, and intestinal contents.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Fermented food and many alcoholic beverages can also contain significant amounts of acetaldehyde.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde, derived from mucosal or microbial oxidation of ethanol, tobacco smoke, and diet, appears to act as a cumulative carcinogen in the upper digestive tract of humans.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] According to European Commission's Scientific Committee on Consumer Safety's (SCCS) "Opinion on Acetaldehyde" (2012) the cosmetic products special risk limit is 5 mg/L and acetaldehyde should not be used in mouth-washing products.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde can be produced by the photo-oxidation of polyethylene terephthalate (PET), via a Type II Norrish reaction.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] Although the levels produced by this process are minute acetaldehyde has an exceedingly low taste/odor threshold of around 20–40 ppb and can cause an off-taste in bottled water.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] The level at which an average consumer could detect acetaldehyde is still considerably lower than any toxicity.
[src:ammonia/acetaldehyde] The yeast *Candida albicans* in patients with potentially carcinogenic oral diseases has been shown to produce acetaldehyde in quantities sufficient to cause problems.
[src:ammonia/acetamide] Alternatively acetamide can be obtained in excellent yield via ammonolysis of acetylacetone under conditions commonly used in reductive amination.
[src:ammonia/acetamide] It can also be made from anhydrous acetic acid, acetonitrile and very well dried hydrogen chloride gas, using an ice bath, alongside more valuable reagent acetyl chloride.
[src:ammonia/acetamide] Yield is typically low (up to 35%), and the acetamide made this way is generated as a salt with HCl.
[src:ammonia/acetamide] Acetamide is used as a plasticizer and an industrial solvent.
[src:ammonia/acetamide] Molten acetamide is good solvent with a broad range of applicability.
[src:ammonia/acetamide] Notably, its dielectric constant is higher than most organic solvents, allowing it to dissolve inorganic compounds with solubilities closely analogous to that of water.
[src:ammonia/acetamide] Acetamide has uses in electrochemistry and the organic synthesis of pharmaceuticals, pesticides, and antioxidants for plastics.
[src:ammonia/acetamide] Acetamide has been detected near the center of the Milky Way galaxy.
[src:ammonia/acetamide] This finding is potentially significant because acetamide has an amide bond, similar to the essential bond between amino acids in proteins.
[src:ammonia/acetamide] This finding lends support to the theory that organic molecules that can lead to life (as we know it on Earth) can form in space.
[src:ammonia/acetamide] In addition, acetamide is found infrequently on burning coal dumps, as a mineral of the same name.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is the second simplest carboxylic acid (after formic acid).
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] It is an important chemical reagent and industrial chemical across various fields, used primarily in the production of cellulose acetate for photographic film, polyvinyl acetate for wood glue, and synthetic fibres and fabrics.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] In households, diluted acetic acid is often used in descaling agents.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] In the food industry, acetic acid is controlled by the food additive code E260 as an acidity regulator and as a condiment.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] In biochemistry, the acetyl group, derived from acetic acid, is fundamental to all forms of life.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] When bound to coenzyme A, it is central to the metabolism of carbohydrates and fats.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] The global demand for acetic acid as of 2023 is about 17.88 million metric tonnes per year (t/a).
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Most of the world's acetic acid is produced via the carbonylation of methanol.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Its production and subsequent industrial use poses health hazards to workers, including incidental skin damage and chronic respiratory injuries from inhalation.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] The trivial name "acetic acid" is the most commonly used and preferred IUPAC name.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] The systematic name "ethanoic acid", a valid IUPAC name, is constructed according to the substitutive nomenclature.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] The name "acetic acid" derives from the Latin word for vinegar, "*acetum*", which means "to sour" in relation to the bitter taste of fermented fruits.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] "Glacial acetic acid" is a name for water-free (anhydrous) acetic acid.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Similar to the German name "Eisessig" ("ice vinegar"), the name comes from the solid ice-like crystals that form with agitation, slightly below room temperature at 16.6 °C (61.9 °F).
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Acetic acid can never be truly water-free in an atmosphere that contains water, so the presence of 0.1% water in glacial acetic acid lowers its melting point by 0.2 °C.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] A common symbol for acetic acid is AcOH (or HOAc), where Ac is the pseudoelement symbol representing the acetyl group CH3−C(=O)−; the conjugate base, acetate (CH3COO−), is thus represented as AcO−.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Acetate is the ion resulting from loss of H+ from acetic acid.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] The name "acetate" can also refer to a salt containing this anion, or an ester of acetic acid.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] (The symbol Ac for the acetyl functional group is not to be confused with the symbol Ac for the element actinium; context prevents confusion among organic chemists).
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] To better reflect its structure, acetic acid is often written as CH3−C(O)OH, CH3−C(=O)−OH, CH3COOH, and CH3CO2H.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] In the context of acid–base reactions, the abbreviation HAc is sometimes used, where Ac in this case is a symbol for acetate (rather than acetyl).
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] The carboxymethyl functional group derived from removing one hydrogen from the methyl group of acetic acid has the chemical formula −CH2−C(=O)−OH.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Acetic acid, the dilute solution of which is known as vinegar, is likely the first acid to be produced in large quantities in history.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Vinegar has been used for at least 10,000 years as it is the natural result of exposure of beer and wine to air because acetic acid-producing bacteria are present globally.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Hippocrates used vinegar as an antiseptic and as a remedy for numerous conditions including fever, constipation, ulcers, and pleurisy.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Ancient Romans boiled soured wine to produce a highly sweet syrup called *sapa*.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Sapa that was produced in lead pots was rich in lead acetate, a sweet substance also called *sugar of lead* or *sugar of Saturn*, which contributed to lead poisoning among the Roman aristocracy.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] In the 16th-century German alchemist Andreas Libavius described the production of acetone from the dry distillation of lead acetate, ketonic decarboxylation.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] The presence of water in vinegar has such a profound effect on acetic acid's properties that for centuries chemists believed that glacial acetic acid and the acid found in vinegar were two different substances.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] French chemist Pierre Adet proved them identical.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] In 1845 German chemist Hermann Kolbe synthesized acetic acid from inorganic compounds for the first time.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] This reaction sequence consisted of chlorination of carbon disulfide to carbon tetrachloride, followed by pyrolysis to tetrachloroethylene and aqueous chlorination to trichloroacetic acid, and concluded with electrolytic reduction to acetic acid.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] By 1910, most glacial acetic acid was obtained from pyroligneous liquor, a product of the destructive distillation of wood.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] The acetic acid was isolated by treatment with milk of lime, and the resulting calcium acetate was then acidified with sulfuric acid to recover acetic acid.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] At that time, Germany was producing 10,000 tons of glacial acetic acid, around 30% of which was used for the manufacture of indigo dye.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Because both methanol and carbon monoxide are commodity raw materials, methanol carbonylation long appeared to be an attractive method of acetic acid production.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Henri Dreyfus at British Celanese developed a methanol carbonylation pilot plant as early as 1925.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] However, a lack of practical materials that could contain the corrosive reaction mixture at the high pressures needed (200 atm or more) discouraged commercialization of these routes.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] The first commercial methanol carbonylation process, which used a cobalt catalyst, was developed by German chemical company BASF in 1963.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] In 1968, a rhodium-based catalyst (*cis*−[Rh(CO)2I2]−) was discovered that could operate efficiently at lower pressure with almost no by-products.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] US chemical company Monsanto Company built the first plant using this catalyst in 1970, and rhodium-catalyzed methanol carbonylation became the dominant method of acetic acid production (see Monsanto process).
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] In the late 1990s, BP Chemicals commercialized the Cativa catalyst ([Ir(CO)2I2]−), which is promoted by iridium for greater efficiency.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Known as the Cativa process, the iridium-catalyzed production of glacial acetic acid is greener, and has largely supplanted the Monsanto process, often in the same production plants.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Interstellar acetic acid was first detected in the Sagittarius B2 North molecular cloud (also known as the Sgr B2 Large Molecule Heimat source).
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Because of this release of the proton (H+), acetic acid has acidic character.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] In aqueous solution, it has a pKa value of 4.76.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Its conjugate base is acetate (CH3COO−).
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] A 1.0 M solution (about the concentration of domestic vinegar) has a pH of 2.4, indicating that merely 0.4% of the acetic acid molecules are ionized.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] In solid acetic acid, the molecules form chains of individual molecules interconnected by hydrogen bonds.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] In the vapour phase at 120 °C (248 °F), dimers can be detected.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Dimers also occur in the liquid phase in dilute solutions with non-hydrogen-bonding solvents, and to a certain extent in pure acetic acid, but are disrupted by hydrogen-bonding solvents.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] The dissociation enthalpy of the dimer is estimated at 65.0–66.0 kJ/mol, and the dissociation entropy at 154–157 J mol−1 K−1.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Other carboxylic acids engage in similar intermolecular hydrogen bonding interactions.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Liquid acetic acid is a hydrophilic (polar) protic solvent, similar to ethanol and water.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] With a relative static permittivity (dielectric constant) of 6.2, it dissolves not only polar compounds such as inorganic salts and sugars, but also non-polar compounds such as oils as well as polar solutes.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] It is miscible with polar and non-polar solvents such as water, chloroform, and hexane.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] With higher alkanes (starting with octane), acetic acid is not miscible at all compositions, and solubility of acetic acid in alkanes declines with longer n-alkanes.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] The solvent and miscibility properties of acetic acid make it a useful industrial chemical, for example, as a solvent in the production of dimethyl terephthalate.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] At physiological pHs, acetic acid is usually fully ionized to acetate in aqueous solution.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] The acetyl group, formally derived from acetic acid, is fundamental to all forms of life.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Typically, it is bound to coenzyme A by acetyl-CoA synthetase enzymes, where it is central to the metabolism of carbohydrates and fats.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Unlike longer-chain carboxylic acids (the fatty acids), acetic acid does not occur in natural triglycerides.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Most of the acetate generated in cells for use in acetyl-CoA is synthesized directly from ethanol or pyruvate.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] However, the artificial triglyceride triacetin (glycerine triacetate) is a common food additive and is found in cosmetics and topical medicines; this additive is metabolized to glycerol and acetic acid in the body.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is produced and excreted by acetic acid bacteria, notably the genus *Acetobacter* and *Clostridium acetobutylicum*.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] These bacteria are found universally in foodstuffs, water, and soil, and acetic acid is produced naturally as fruits and other foods spoil.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is also a component of the vaginal lubrication of humans and other primates, where it appears to serve as a mild antibacterial agent.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is produced industrially both naturally via bacterial fermentation and synthetically.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] About 75% of acetic acid made for use in the chemical industry is made by the carbonylation of methanol, explained below.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] The biological route accounts for only about 10% of world production, but it remains important for the production of vinegar because many food purity laws require vinegar used in foods to be of biological origin.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Other processes are methyl formate isomerization, conversion of syngas to acetic acid, and gas phase oxidation of ethylene and ethanol.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Acetic acid can be purified via fractional freezing using an ice bath.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] The water and other impurities will remain liquid while the acetic acid will precipitate out.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] As of 2003–2005, total worldwide production of virgin acetic acid was estimated at 5 Mt/a (million tonnes per year), approximately half of which was produced in the United States.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] European production was approximately 1 Mt/a and declining, while Japanese production was 0.7 Mt/a.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Another 1.5 Mt were recycled each year, bringing the total world market to 6.5 Mt/a.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Since then, the global production has increased from 10.7 Mt/a in 2010 to 17.88 Mt/a in 2023.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] The two biggest producers of virgin acetic acid are Celanese and BP Chemicals.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Other major producers include Millennium Chemicals, Sterling Chemicals, Samsung, Eastman, and Svensk Etanolkemi.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Most acetic acid is produced by methanol carbonylation.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] The process involves iodomethane as an intermediate, and occurs in three steps.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] A metal carbonyl catalyst is needed for the carbonylation (step 2).
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Two related processes exist for the carbonylation of methanol: the rhodium-catalyzed Monsanto process, and the iridium-catalyzed Cativa process.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] The latter process is greener and more efficient and has largely supplanted the former process.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Catalytic amounts of water are used in both processes, but the Cativa process requires less, so the water-gas shift reaction is suppressed, and fewer by-products are formed.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] By altering the process conditions, acetic anhydride may also be produced in plants using rhodium catalysis.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Prior to the commercialization of the Monsanto process, most acetic acid was produced by oxidation of acetaldehyde.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] This remains the second-most-important manufacturing method, although it is usually not competitive with the carbonylation of methanol.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] The acetaldehyde can be produced by hydration of acetylene.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] This was the dominant technology in the early 1900s.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Such oxidations require metal catalyst, such as the naphthenate salts of manganese, cobalt, and chromium.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] The typical reaction is conducted at temperatures and pressures designed to be as hot as possible while still keeping the butane a liquid.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Typical reaction conditions are 150 °C (302 °F) and 55 atm.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Side-products may also form, including butanone, ethyl acetate, formic acid, and propionic acid.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] These side-products are also commercially valuable, and the reaction conditions may be altered to produce more of them where needed.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] However, the separation of acetic acid from these by-products adds to the cost of the process.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Similar conditions and catalysts are used for butane oxidation, the oxygen in air to produce acetic acid can oxidize acetaldehyde.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Using modern catalysts, this reaction can have an acetic acid yield greater than 95%.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] The major side-products are ethyl acetate, formic acid, and formaldehyde, all of which have lower boiling points than acetic acid and are readily separated by distillation.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Acetaldehyde may be prepared from ethylene via the Wacker process, and then oxidized as above.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] In more recent times, chemical company Showa Denko, which opened an ethylene oxidation plant in Ōita, Japan, in 1997, commercialized a cheaper single-stage conversion of ethylene to acetic acid.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] The process is catalyzed by a palladium metal catalyst supported on a heteropoly acid such as silicotungstic acid.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] It is thought to be competitive with methanol carbonylation for smaller plants (100–250 kt/a), depending on the local price of ethylene.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] For most of human history, acetic acid bacteria of the genus *Acetobacter* have made acetic acid, in the form of vinegar.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Given sufficient oxygen, these bacteria can produce vinegar from a variety of alcoholic foodstuffs.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Commonly used feeds include apple cider, wine, and fermented grain, malt, rice, or potato mashes.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] A dilute alcohol solution inoculated with *Acetobacter* and kept in a warm, airy place will become vinegar over the course of a few months.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Industrial vinegar-making methods accelerate this process by improving the supply of oxygen to the bacteria.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] The first batches of vinegar produced by fermentation probably followed errors in the winemaking process.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] If must is fermented at too high a temperature, acetobacter will overwhelm the yeast naturally occurring on the grapes.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] As the demand for vinegar for culinary, medical, and sanitary purposes increased, vintners quickly learned to use other organic materials to produce vinegar in the hot summer months before the grapes were ripe and ready for processing into wine.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] This method was slow, however, and not always successful, as the vintners did not understand the process.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] One of the first modern commercial processes was the "fast method" or "German method", first practised in Germany in 1823.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] In this process, fermentation takes place in a tower packed with wood shavings or charcoal.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] The alcohol-containing feed is trickled into the top of the tower, and fresh air supplied from the bottom by either natural or forced convection.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] The improved air supply in this process cut the time to prepare vinegar from months to weeks.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Nowadays, most vinegar is made in submerged tank culture, first described in 1949 by Otto Hromatka and Heinrich Ebner.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] In this method, alcohol is fermented to vinegar in a continuously stirred tank, and oxygen is supplied by bubbling air through the solution.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Using modern applications of this method, vinegar of 15% acetic acid can be prepared in only 24 hours in batch process, even 20% in 60-hour fed-batch process.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Species of anaerobic bacteria, including members of the genus *Clostridium* or *Acetobacterium*, can convert sugars to acetic acid directly without creating ethanol as an intermediate.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] This ability of *Clostridium* to metabolize sugars directly, or to produce acetic acid from less costly inputs, suggests that these bacteria could produce acetic acid more efficiently than ethanol-oxidizers like *Acetobacter*.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] However, *Clostridium* bacteria are less acid-tolerant than *Acetobacter*.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Even the most acid-tolerant *Clostridium* strains can produce vinegar in concentrations of only a few percent, compared to *Acetobacter* strains that can produce vinegar in concentrations up to 20%.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] At present, it remains more cost-effective to produce vinegar using *Acetobacter*, rather than using *Clostridium* and concentrating it.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] As a result, although acetogenic bacteria have been known since 1940, their industrial use is confined to a few niche applications.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is a chemical reagent for the production of chemical compounds.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] The largest single use of acetic acid is in the production of vinyl acetate monomer, closely followed by acetic anhydride and ester production.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] The volume of acetic acid used in vinegar is comparatively small.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] The primary use of acetic acid is the production of vinyl acetate monomer (VAM).
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] In 2008, this application was estimated to consume a third of the world's production of acetic acid.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] The reaction consists of ethylene and acetic acid with oxygen over a palladium catalyst, conducted in the gas phase.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Vinyl acetate can be polymerized to polyvinyl acetate or other polymers, which are components in paints and adhesives.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] The major esters of acetic acid are commonly used as solvents for inks, paints and coatings.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] The esters include ethyl acetate, *n*-butyl acetate, isobutyl acetate, and propyl acetate.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] For example, acetic acid and ethanol gives ethyl acetate and water.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Most acetate esters, however, are produced from acetaldehyde using the Tishchenko reaction.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] In addition, ether acetates are used as solvents for nitrocellulose, acrylic lacquers, varnish removers, and wood stains.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] First, glycol monoethers are produced from ethylene oxide or propylene oxide with alcohol, which are then esterified with acetic acid.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] The three major products are ethylene glycol monoethyl ether acetate (EEA), ethylene glycol monobutyl ether acetate (EBA), and propylene glycol monomethyl ether acetate (PMA, more commonly known as PGMEA in semiconductor manufacturing processes, where it is used as a resist solvent).
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] This application consumes about 15% to 20% of worldwide acetic acid.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Ether acetates, for example EEA, have been shown to be harmful to human reproduction.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] The product of the condensation of two molecules of acetic acid is acetic anhydride.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] The worldwide production of acetic anhydride is a major application, and uses approximately 25% to 30% of the global production of acetic acid.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] The main process involves dehydration of acetic acid to give ketene at 700–750 °C.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Acetic anhydride is an acetylation agent.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] As such, its major application is for cellulose acetate, a synthetic textile also used for photographic film, which is produced by reacting cellulose with acetic acid and acetic anhydride in the presence of sulfuric acid.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Acetic anhydride is also a reagent for the production of heroin and other compounds.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] As a polar protic solvent, acetic acid is frequently used for recrystallization to purify organic compounds.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is used as a solvent in the production of terephthalic acid (TPA), the raw material for polyethylene terephthalate (PET).
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] In 2006, about 20% of acetic acid was used for TPA production.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is often used as a solvent for reactions involving carbocations, such as Friedel-Crafts alkylation.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] For example, one stage in the commercial manufacture of synthetic camphor involves a Wagner-Meerwein rearrangement of camphene to isobornyl acetate; here acetic acid acts both as a solvent and as a nucleophile to trap the rearranged carbocation.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Glacial acetic acid is used in analytical chemistry for the estimation of weakly alkaline substances such as organic amides.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Glacial acetic acid is a much weaker base than water, so the amide behaves as a strong base in this medium.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] It then can be titrated using a solution in glacial acetic acid of a very strong acid, such as perchloric acid.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Acetic acid injection into a tumor has been used to treat cancer since the 1800s.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is used as part of cervical cancer screening in many areas in the developing world.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] The acid is applied to the cervix and if an area of white appears after about a minute the test is positive.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is an effective antiseptic when used as a 1% solution, with broad spectrum of activity against streptococci, staphylococci, pseudomonas, enterococci and others.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] It may be used to treat skin infections caused by pseudomonas strains resistant to typical antibiotics.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] While diluted acetic acid is used in iontophoresis, no high quality evidence supports this treatment for rotator cuff disease.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] As a treatment for otitis externa, it is on the World Health Organization's List of Essential Medicines.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Vinegar is typically no less than 4% acetic acid by mass.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Legal limits on acetic acid content vary by jurisdiction.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Vinegar is used directly as a condiment, and in the pickling of vegetables and other foods.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Table vinegar tends to be more diluted (4% to 8% acetic acid), while commercial food pickling employs solutions that are more concentrated.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] The proportion of acetic acid used worldwide as vinegar is not as large as industrial uses, but it is by far the oldest and best-known application.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Acetic acid undergoes the typical chemical reactions of a carboxylic acid.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Upon treatment with a standard base, it converts to metal acetate and water.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] With strong bases (e.g., organolithium reagents), it can be doubly deprotonated to give LiCH2COOLi.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] The OH group is the main site of reaction, as illustrated by the conversion of acetic acid to acetyl chloride.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Other substitution derivatives include acetic anhydride; this anhydride is produced by loss of water from two molecules of acetic acid.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Esters of acetic acid can likewise be formed via Fischer esterification, and amides can be formed.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Because aluminium forms a passivating acid-resistant film of aluminium oxide, aluminium tanks are used to transport acetic acid.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Containers lined with glass, stainless steel or polyethylene are also used for this purpose.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] A colour reaction for salts of acetic acid is iron(III) chloride solution, which results in a deeply red colour that disappears after acidification.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] A more sensitive test uses lanthanum nitrate with iodine and ammonia to give a blue solution.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Acetates when heated with arsenic trioxide form cacodyl oxide, which can be detected by its malodorous vapours.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Organic or inorganic salts are produced from acetic acid.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Halogenated acetic acids are produced from acetic acid.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Amounts of acetic acid used in these other applications together account for another 5–10% of acetic acid use worldwide.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Prolonged inhalation exposure (eight hours) to acetic acid vapours at 10 ppm can produce some irritation of eyes, nose, and throat; at 100 ppm marked lung irritation and possible damage to lungs, eyes, and skin may result.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Vapour concentrations of 1,000 ppm cause marked irritation of eyes, nose and upper respiratory tract and cannot be tolerated.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] These predictions were based on animal experiments and industrial exposure.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] In 12 workers exposed for two or more years to an airborne average concentration of 51 ppm acetic acid (estimated), symptoms of conjunctive irritation, upper respiratory tract irritation, and hyperkeratotic dermatitis were produced.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Exposure to 50 ppm or more is intolerable to most persons and results in intensive lacrimation and irritation of the eyes, nose, and throat, with pharyngeal oedema and chronic bronchitis.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Unacclimatized humans experience extreme eye and nasal irritation at concentrations in excess of 25 ppm, and conjunctivitis from concentrations below 10 ppm has been reported.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Concentrated acetic acid (≥ 25%) is corrosive to skin.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] These burns or blisters may not appear until hours after exposure.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] The hazardous properties of acetic acid are dependent on the concentration of the (typically aqueous) solution, with the most significant increases in hazard levels at thresholds of 25% and 90% acetic acid concentration by weight.
[src:ammonia/acetic-acid] Concentrated acetic acid can be ignited only with difficulty at standard temperature and pressure, but becomes a flammable risk in temperatures greater than 39 °C (102 °F), and can form explosive mixtures with air at increased temperatures with explosive limits of 5.4–16% concentration.
[src:ammonia/acgih] The **American Conference of Governmental Industrial Hygienists** (**ACGIH**) is a professional association of industrial hygienists and practitioners of related professions, with headquarters in Cincinnati, Ohio.
[src:ammonia/acgih] One of its goals is to advance worker protection by providing timely, objective, scientific information to occupational and environmental health professionals.
[src:ammonia/acgih] The National Conference of Governmental Industrial Hygienists (NCGIH) convened on June 27, 1938, in Washington, D.C.
[src:ammonia/acgih] NCGIH's original constitution limited full membership to two representatives from each governmental industrial hygiene agency.
[src:ammonia/acgih] Associate membership was made available to other professional personnel of the agencies holding full memberships, and also to personnel of educational institutions engaged in teaching industrial hygiene.
[src:ammonia/acgih] Governmental industrial hygiene personnel of other countries were eligible for affiliated membership.
[src:ammonia/acgih] The Conference came into being with 59 members, one affiliated member, and 16 associate members.
[src:ammonia/acgih] Forty-three members, one associate and six guests, attended the initial Conference.
[src:ammonia/acgih] All but five of the members were from health departments.
[src:ammonia/acgih] The New York and Massachusetts state labor departments each had two present, and one from the West Virginia state compensation commission.
[src:ammonia/acgih] At the end of World War II, many individuals were leaving governmental employment and membership in the Conference declined from the peak of 281 in 1944 to 235 in 1946.
[src:ammonia/acgih] Changes due to the transition to a peacetime economy, the development of other professional associations, and changes in the technical and administrative needs of state and local agencies, required the Conference to revise its constitution and make some major changes in its organizational structure.
[src:ammonia/acgih] The 1946 constitution revisions abandoned the concept of limiting full membership to only two individuals from each governmental industrial hygiene agency.
[src:ammonia/acgih] This opened the doors to all of their professional personnel to participate in the activities of the organization on an equal basis.
[src:ammonia/acgih] Governmental industrial hygiene personnel from foreign countries were also given the right to full membership.
[src:ammonia/acgih] These changes, among others, were to have a salutary effect on the organization which, in 1946, changed its name to the American Conference of Governmental Industrial Hygienists (ACGIH).
[src:ammonia/acgih] In the mid-1950s, steady growth in membership resumed and by 1960 there were 511 members, including 54 from other countries.
[src:ammonia/acgih] During the next decade these numbers more than doubled and in 1977 the total reached 1,800, of which 166 were from outside the United States.
[src:ammonia/acgih] For over 75 years, ACGIH has been dedicated to the industrial hygiene and occupational and environmental health and safety communities.
[src:ammonia/acgih] They have grown and expanded without losing sight of their original goal - to encourage the interchange of experience among industrial hygiene workers and to collect and make accessible such information and data as might be of aid to them in the proper fulfillment of their duties.
[src:ammonia/acgih] This original goal is reflected in both their current mission - the advancement of occupational and environmental health - and in their tagline: Defining the Science of Occupational and Environmental Health.
[src:ammonia/acgih] As of 2016, nine ACGIH committees focus their energies on a range of topics: agricultural safety and health, air sampling instruments, bioaerosols, biological exposure indices, industrial ventilation, international, small business, chemical substance TLVs, and physical agent TLVs.
[src:ammonia/acgih] The *Applied Occupational and Environmental Hygiene* journal, was published from 1990 through 2003 and was formerly published as *Applied Industrial Hygiene* from 1986 through 1989.
[src:ammonia/acgih] This ACGIH peer-reviewed journal provided scientific information and data to members until ACGIH and AIHA began publishing a joint journal.
[src:ammonia/acgih] The *Journal of Occupational and Environmental Hygiene* (JOEH) is a joint publication of the American Industrial Hygiene Association (AIHA) and ACGIH.
[src:ammonia/acgih] JOEH is a peer-reviewed journal devoted to enhancing the knowledge and practice of occupational and environmental hygiene and safety by widely disseminating research articles and applied studies of the highest quality.
[src:ammonia/acgih] The activities of each Committee are directed by an individual mission statement.
[src:ammonia/acgih] Mission - To promote those activities and programs necessary to our suited for agriculture or agro-business and to increase awareness of occupational health, safety, and environmental issues affecting this underserved population worldwide.
[src:ammonia/acgih] Mission - To report on the availability, efficiency, use, and limitations of existing and new sampling methodology and instrumentation.
[src:ammonia/acgih] Mission - To compile and disseminate information on biologically derived contaminants that may become airborne, to develop recommendations for assessment, control, remediation, and prevention of such hazards, and to establish criteria for bioaerosol exposure limits.
[src:ammonia/acgih] Mission - To develop occupational biological exposure guidelines that are scientifically valid and supported by professional judgment, up-to-date, well-documented, understandable, clear, and produced by a clearly defined process that is balanced and free of conflict of interest.
[src:ammonia/acgih] Mission - To provide a safe and healthful environment by integrating state-of-the-art information from government and industry sources, using them to develop and recommend ventilation and other engineering controls to capture, collect, filter, and remove airborne contaminants from the workplace.
[src:ammonia/acgih] Mission - To help develop and support ACGIH's international initiatives.
[src:ammonia/acgih] Mission - To develop and disseminate practical information that operators of small businesses and their employees can apply to the recognition, evaluation, and control of workplace hazards and to assist education safety and health professionals in working with small business concerns.
[src:ammonia/acgih] Mission - To recommend airborne concentrations of agents and exposure conditions for use in the practice of industrial hygiene and by other qualified professionals to protect worker health.
[src:ammonia/acgih] Mission - To develop and disseminate occupational exposure guidelines that are evidence-based, scientifically valid, and rigorously review.
[src:ammonia/acgih] ACGIH establishes the Threshold Limit Values (TLVs) for chemical substances, physical agents, and Biological Exposure Indices (BEIs); which refer to the airborne concentrations of chemical substances that workers can be safely exposed to over their working lifetime.
[src:ammonia/acgih] They are divided into four categories: time-weighted average (TWA), short-term exposure limit (STEL), surface limit (SL), and ceiling (C).
[src:ammonia/acgih] The Threshold Limit Values for Chemical Substances (TLV-CS) Committee was established in 1941.
[src:ammonia/acgih] This group was charged with investigating, recommending, and annually reviewing exposure limits for chemical substances.
[src:ammonia/acgih] Two years later, the organization adopted its first list of 148 exposure limits, then referred to as Maximum Allowable Concentrations.
[src:ammonia/acgih] The term "Threshold Limit Values (TLV) was introduced in 1956.
[src:ammonia/acgih] The first list of Threshold Limit Values and Biological Exposure Indices (the *TLVs and BEIs* book) was published in 1962*.* A new edition is now published annually.
[src:ammonia/acgih] Today's list of TLVs and BEIs includes over 600 chemical substances and physical agents, as well as over 30 Biological Exposure Indices for selected chemicals.
[src:ammonia/acgih] The TLVs and BEIs are developed as guidelines to assist in the control of health hazards.
[src:ammonia/acgih] These recommendations or guidelines are intended for use in the practice of industrial hygiene, to be interpreted and applied only by a person trained in this discipline.
[src:ammonia/acgih] While not enforceable like OSHA's "permissible limit exposures", TLVs and BEIs are still significant and act as advisory numbers to OSHA and to manufacturers who care about workplace safety.
[src:ammonia/acgih] In certain circumstances, individuals or organizations may wish to make use of these recommendations or guidelines if the use of TLVs and BEIs contributes to the overall improvement in worker protection.
[src:ammonia/acgih] The Foundation for Occupational Health & Safety (FOHS) is an ACGIH supported nonprofit that promotes workplace and worker well-being worldwide through professional education, scientific research in the field and on the profession itself, and the creation of the Sustainable TLV/BEI Fund.
[src:ammonia/acgih] In 2003, the YIHWAG Family Foundation awarded FOHS a substantial grant to benefit the needs of educational organizations in developing countries throughout the world.
[src:ammonia/acgih] From this grant, FOHS established the Worldwide Outreach Program.
[src:ammonia/acgih] Its mission is to support the professional development of occupational health and safety throughout the world.
[src:ammonia/acgih] Qualifying educational organizations, professional organizations, and non-government organizations seeking to further the goals of the World Health Organization Collaborating Centers for Occupational Health’s 2006-2010 Work Plan can apply for program grants ranging from $1,000 - $2,000.
[src:ammonia/acgih] In 2008, FOHS created the Sustainable TLV/BEI Fund.
[src:ammonia/acgih] The core purpose of the fund is to develop sustainable financial support to ensure the continued existence of ACGIH® TLVs and BEIs.
[src:ammonia/acgih] Since its inception the core purpose and ‘cause’ of ACGIH has been to protect workplace employees through the development of science-based occupational exposure guidelines widely known as the TLVs and BEIs.
[src:ammonia/acgih] These guidelines have become recognized throughout the world as forming the scientific basis for subsequent development of workplace standards.
[src:ammonia/acwa-power] Its energy portfolio includes thermal power plants, solar power plants (photovoltaic (PV) and concentrated solar power (CSP)), wind, water desalination plants, and green hydrogen projects.
[src:ammonia/acwa-power] Headquartered in Saudi Arabia, ACWA Power maintains regional offices in Riyadh, Jeddah, Dubai, Baku, Beijing, Cairo, Addis Abbaba, Jakarta, Amman, Rabat, Muscat, Johannesburg, Istanbul, Tashkent, and Hanoi.
[src:ammonia/acwa-power] It invests in, develops, co-owns and operates a portfolio of +100 projects with the capacity of 78.85 GW of power and produce 9.5 million m3 /day of desalinated water.
[src:ammonia/acwa-power] ACWA Power and its subsidiary operating companies employ around 4,000 people in projects in 14 different countries.
[src:ammonia/acwa-power] In January 2026, the company officially changed its trading name from ACWA Power to Acwa and unveiled a new brand identity.
[src:ammonia/acwa-power] This rebranding marked the company’s transition from a regional Saudi Arabian developer to a global infrastructure platform managing over US$115 billion in assets across 15 countries.
[src:ammonia/acwa-power] The refreshed identity is built around the "energy quadrilemma" of affordability, sustainability, security, and speed.
[src:ammonia/acwa-power] Coinciding with the rebrand, Acwa announced a strategic goal to double its assets under management to US$250 billion by 2030, focusing on large-scale green hydrogen, next-generation desalination, and renewable energy storage.
[src:ammonia/acwa-power] ACWA Power's board of directors is chaired by Mohammad Abdullah Abunayyan, with Raad Al Saady as its Vice Chairman and Managing Director, and Marco Arcelli as its CEO.
[src:ammonia/acwa-power] In 2002, the Government of Saudi Arabia changed the regulations so that the private sector was permitted to own and operate utilities such as water and power plants.
[src:ammonia/acwa-power] The company was reorganised in 2008 in its current legal form as ACWA Power Company.
[src:ammonia/acwa-power] From 2004 to 2011, ACWA Power focused primarily on Saudi Arabia, and was awarded contracts for several thermal power projects – including the Shuaibah IWPP, Shuqaiq 2 IWPP, Rabigh IPP and Marafiq IPP.
[src:ammonia/acwa-power] Today, ACWA Power operates across 14 countries in the Middle East, Africa, Central Asia, and Southeast Asia, with a portfolio comprising renewable energy, water desalination, green hydrogen, and conventional energy projects.
[src:ammonia/acwa-power] In 2018, the Public Investment Fund (PIF) of Saudi Arabia acquired a 15% stake in ACWA Power and has progressively increased its shareholding to 44%, reinforcing ACWA Power’s pivotal role in achieving the Kingdom’s Vision 2030 energy transition goals.
[src:ammonia/acwa-power] The Noor solar complex in Ouarzazate, Morocco, comprises 510 MW of CSP capacity and 135 MW of solar PV.
[src:ammonia/acwa-power] It was the largest CSP complex globally as of 2019.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia, either directly or indirectly, is also a building block for the synthesis of many chemicals.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] In many countries, it is classified as an extremely hazardous substance.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia is toxic, causing damage to cells and tissues.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] For this reason it is excreted by most animals in the urine, in the form of dissolved urea.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia is produced biologically in a process called nitrogen fixation, but even more is generated industrially by the Haber process.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The process helped revolutionise agriculture by providing cheap fertilizers.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The global industrial production of ammonia in 2021 was 235 million tonnes.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Industrial ammonia is transported by road in tankers, by rail in tank wagons, by sea in gas carriers, or in cylinders.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia occurs in nature and has been detected in the interstellar medium.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia boils at −33.34 °C (−28.012 °F) at a pressure of one atmosphere, but the liquid can often be handled in the laboratory without external cooling.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Household ammonia or ammonium hydroxide is a solution of ammonia in water.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The name *ammonia* is derived from the name of the Egyptian deity *Amun* (*Ammon* in Greek) since priests and travellers of those temples would burn soils rich in ammonium chloride, which came from animal dung and urine.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Pliny, in Book XXXI of his Natural History, refers to a salt named *hammoniacum*, so called because of the proximity of its source to the Temple of Jupiter Amun (Greek Ἄμμων *Ammon*) in the Roman province of Cyrenaica.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] However, the description Pliny gives of the salt does not conform to the properties of ammonium chloride.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] According to Herbert Hoover's commentary in his English translation of Georgius Agricola's *De re metallica*, it is likely to have been common sea salt.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] In any case, that salt ultimately gave ammonia and ammonium compounds their name.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Substances containing ammonia, or those that are similar to it, are called *ammoniacal*.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia arises in the atmosphere from both anthropogenic and natural sources.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The prevalent source is agriculture at around 80%.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] This includes fertilizers, urea produced by livestock, and manure in order of contribution.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Biomass burning also contributes to atmospheric ammonia, with forest fires and agricultural waste burning emitting roughly the same amount of ammonia into the atmosphere.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia can be emitted naturally from soils and plants when the concentration of ammonia in the soil or plant is higher than the concentration of ammonia in the air.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] This is known as one part of the bi-directional exchange model.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The dominant sink for atmospheric ammonia is rain.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] In soil, ammonia-oxidizing archaea (AOA) and ammonia-oxidizing bacteria (AOB) convert ammonia into nitrite.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The atmospheric lifetime of ammonia through these processes vary from 12 to 48 hours.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Atmospheric ammonia gives sulfate-nitrate aerosols through reactions with sulfuric acid and nitric acid, with ammonium sulfate being prominent in this process due to its low vapour pressure.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] These aerosols affect the climate and can impact human health.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The lifetime of ammonia through oxidisation is much longer than through deposition, with it being as low as 30 days.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The amino radical then can be oxidised by multiple compounds to form greenhouse gases, such as nitrous oxide.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The oxidation of ammonia may also result in the production of nitric oxide, increasing NOx levels significantly in rural areas where relative levels are typically lower compared to urban areas.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia is a colourless gas with a characteristically pungent smell.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] It is lighter than air, its density being 0.589 times that of air.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] It is easily liquefied due to the strong hydrogen bonding between molecules.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Gaseous ammonia turns to a colourless liquid, which boils at −33.1 °C (−27.58 °F), and freezes to colourless crystals at −77.7 °C (−107.86 °F).
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Little data is available at very high temperatures and pressures, but the liquid-vapor critical point occurs at 405 K and 11.35 MPa.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The crystal symmetry is cubic, Pearson symbol cP16, space group P213 No.198, lattice constant 0.5125 nm.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Liquid ammonia possesses strong ionising powers reflecting its high *ε* of 22 at −35 °C (−31 °F).
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] In an aqueous solution, it can be expelled by boiling.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The aqueous solution of ammonia is basic, and may be described as aqueous ammonia or ammonium hydroxide.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The maximum concentration of ammonia in water (a saturated solution) has a specific gravity of 0.880 and is often known as '.880 ammonia'.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Liquid ammonia is a widely studied nonaqueous ionising solvent.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Its most conspicuous property is its ability to dissolve alkali metals to form highly coloured, electrically conductive solutions containing solvated electrons.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Apart from these remarkable solutions, much of the chemistry in liquid ammonia can be classified by analogy with related reactions in aqueous solutions.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Comparison of the physical properties of NH3 with those of water shows NH3 has the lower melting point, boiling point, density, viscosity, dielectric constant and electrical conductivity.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] These differences are attributed at least in part to the weaker hydrogen bonding in NH3.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The ionic self-dissociation constant of liquid NH3 at −50 °C is about 10−33.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Liquid ammonia is an ionising solvent, although less so than water, and dissolves a range of ionic compounds, including many nitrates, nitrites, cyanides, thiocyanates, metal cyclopentadienyl complexes and metal bis(trimethylsilyl)amides.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Most ammonium salts are soluble and act as acids in liquid ammonia solutions.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The solubility of halide salts increases from fluoride to iodide.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] A saturated solution of ammonium nitrate (**Divers' solution**, named after Edward Divers) contains 0.83 mol solute per mole of ammonia and has a vapour pressure of less than 1 bar even at 25 °C (77 °F).
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] However, few oxyanion salts with other cations dissolve.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Liquid ammonia will dissolve all of the alkali metals and other electropositive metals such as Ca, Sr, Ba, Eu and Yb (also Mg using an electrolytic process).
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] At low concentrations (<0.06 mol/L), deep blue solutions are formed: these contain metal cations and solvated electrons, free electrons that are surrounded by a cage of ammonia molecules.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] These solutions are strong reducing agents.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] At higher concentrations, the solutions are metallic in appearance and in electrical conductivity.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] At low temperatures, the two types of solution can coexist as immiscible phases.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] In practice, both oxidation to dinitrogen and reduction to dihydrogen are slow, although ammonia in principle is labile under both conditions.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Although oxidation of liquid ammonia is usually slow, there is still a risk of explosion, particularly if transition metal ions are present as possible catalysts.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The stability of ammonia under reducing conditions is evidenced by the slow (hours) decomposition of solutions containing alkali metals.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The ammonia molecule has a trigonal pyramidal shape, as predicted by the valence shell electron pair repulsion theory (VSEPR theory) with an experimentally determined bond angle of 106.7°.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The central nitrogen atom has five outer electrons with an additional electron from each hydrogen atom.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] This gives a total of eight electrons, or four electron pairs that are arranged tetrahedrally.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Three of these electron pairs are used as bond pairs, which leaves one lone pair of electrons.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The lone pair repels more strongly than bond pairs; therefore, the bond angle is not 109.5°, as expected for a regular tetrahedral arrangement, but 106.7°.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] This shape gives the molecule a dipole moment and makes it polar.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The molecule's polarity, and especially its ability to form hydrogen bonds, makes ammonia highly miscible with water.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The lone pair makes ammonia a base, a proton acceptor.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia is moderately basic; a 1.0 M aqueous solution has a pH of 11.6, and if a strong acid is added to such a solution until the solution is neutral (pH = 7), 99.4% of the ammonia molecules are protonated.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Temperature and salinity also affect the proportion of ammonium [NH4]+.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The latter has the shape of a regular tetrahedron and is isoelectronic with methane.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The ammonia molecule readily undergoes nitrogen inversion at room temperature; a useful analogy is an umbrella turning itself inside out in a strong wind.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The energy barrier to this inversion is 24.7 kJ/mol, and the resonance frequency is 23.79 GHz, corresponding to microwave radiation of a wavelength of 1.260 cm.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The absorption at this frequency was the first microwave spectrum to be observed and was used in the first maser.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] One of the most characteristic properties of ammonia is its basicity.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia is considered to be a weak base.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] It combines with acids to form ammonium salts.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Thus, with hydrochloric acid it forms ammonium chloride, with nitric acid, ammonium nitrate, etc.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Perfectly dry ammonia gas will not combine with perfectly dry hydrogen chloride gas; moisture is necessary to bring about the reaction.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Although ammonia is well known as a weak base, it can also act as an extremely weak acid.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] It is a protic substance and is capable of formation of amides (which contain the NH−2 ion).
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia often functions as a weak base, so it has some buffering ability.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Shifts in pH will cause more or fewer ammonium cations (NH+4) and amide anions (NH−2) to be present in solution.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia does not burn readily or sustain combustion, except under narrow fuel-to-air mixtures of 15–28% ammonia by volume in air.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] When mixed with oxygen, it burns with a pale yellowish-green flame.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ignition occurs when chlorine is passed into ammonia, forming nitrogen and hydrogen chloride; if chlorine is present in excess, then the highly explosive nitrogen trichloride (NCl3) is also formed.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The standard enthalpy change of combustion, Δ*H*°c, expressed per mole of ammonia and with condensation of the water formed, is −382.81 kJ/mol.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Dinitrogen is the thermodynamic product of combustion: all nitrogen oxides are unstable with respect to N2 and O2, which is the principle behind the catalytic converter.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] However, recent studies have shown that efficient and stable combustion of ammonia can be achieved using swirl combustors, thereby rekindling research interest in ammonia as a fuel for thermal power production.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The flammable range of ammonia in dry air is 15.15–27.35% and in 100% relative humidity air is 15.95–26.55%.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] For studying the kinetics of ammonia combustion, knowledge of a detailed reliable reaction mechanism is required, but this has been challenging to obtain.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia is a direct or indirect precursor to most manufactured nitrogen-containing compounds.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] It is the precursor to nitric acid, which is the source for most N-substituted aromatic compounds.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Its ring-opening reaction with ethylene oxide give ethanolamine, diethanolamine, and triethanolamine.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Amides can be prepared by the reaction of ammonia with carboxylic acid and their derivatives.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] For example, ammonia reacts with formic acid (HCOOH) to yield formamide (HCONH2) when heated.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Acyl chlorides are the most reactive, but the ammonia must be present in at least a twofold excess to neutralise the hydrogen chloride formed.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Esters and anhydrides also react with ammonia to form amides.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonium salts of carboxylic acids can be dehydrated to amides by heating to 150–200 °C as long as no thermally sensitive groups are present.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Other organonitrogen compounds include alprazolam, ethanolamine, ethyl carbamate and hexamethylenetetramine.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Nitric acid is generated via the Ostwald process by oxidation of ammonia with air over a platinum catalyst at 700–850 °C (1,292–1,562 °F), ≈9 atm.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Nitric acid is used for the production of fertilisers, explosives, and many organonitrogen compounds.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The hydrogen in ammonia is susceptible to replacement by a myriad substituents.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] With alkenes and with alcohols, ammonia gives alkylamines.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] With chlorine, monochloramine is formed.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Pentavalent ammonia is known as λ5-amine, nitrogen pentahydride decomposes spontaneously into trivalent ammonia (λ3-amine) and hydrogen gas at normal conditions.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] This substance was once investigated as a possible solid rocket fuel in 1966.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia is a ligand forming metal ammine complexes.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] For historical reasons, ammonia is named **ammine** in the nomenclature of coordination compounds.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] One notable ammine complex is cisplatin (Pt(NH3)2Cl2, a widely used anticancer drug.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammine complexes of chromium(III) formed the basis of Alfred Werner's revolutionary theory on the structure of coordination compounds.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Werner noted only two isomers (*fac*- and *mer*-) of the complex [CrCl3(NH3)3] could be formed, and concluded the ligands must be arranged around the metal ion at the vertices of an octahedron.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia forms 1:1 adducts with a variety of Lewis acids such as I2, phenol, and Al(CH3)3.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia is a hard base (HSAB theory) and its E & C parameters are EB = 2.31 and CB = 2.04.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Its relative donor strength toward a series of acids, versus other Lewis bases, can be illustrated by C-B plots.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Sulfur sticks are burnt to detect small leaks in industrial ammonia refrigeration systems.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] In a laboratorial setting, gaseous ammonia can be detected by using concentrated hydrochloric acid or gaseous hydrogen chloride.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] A dense white fume (which is ammonium chloride vapour) arises from the reaction between ammonia and HCl.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The ancient Greek historian Herodotus mentioned that there were outcrops of salt in an area of Libya that was inhabited by a people called the 'Ammonians' (now the Siwa oasis in northwestern Egypt, where salt lakes still exist).
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The Greek geographer Strabo also mentioned the salt from this region.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] However, the ancient authors Dioscorides, Apicius, Arrian, Synesius, and Aëtius of Amida described this salt as forming clear crystals that could be used for cooking and that were essentially rock salt.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] *Hammoniacus sal* appears in the writings of Pliny, although it is not known whether the term is equivalent to the more modern sal ammoniac (ammonium chloride).
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The fermentation of urine by bacteria produces a solution of ammonia; hence fermented urine was used in Classical Antiquity to wash cloth and clothing, to remove hair from hides in preparation for tanning, to serve as a mordant in dyeing cloth, and to remove rust from iron.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] It was also used by ancient dentists to wash teeth.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] In the form of sal ammoniac (نشادر, *nushadir*), ammonia was important to the Muslim alchemists.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] It was mentioned in the *Book of Stones*, likely written in the 9th century and attributed to Jābir ibn Hayyān.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] It was also important to the European alchemists of the 13th century, being mentioned by Albertus Magnus.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] It was also used by dyers in the Middle Ages in the form of fermented urine to alter the colour of vegetable dyes.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] In the 15th century, Basilius Valentinus showed that ammonia could be obtained by the action of alkalis on sal ammoniac.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] At a later period, when sal ammoniac was obtained by distilling the hooves and horns of oxen and neutralising the resulting carbonate with hydrochloric acid, the name 'spirit of hartshorn' was applied to ammonia.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Gaseous ammonia was first isolated by Joseph Black in 1756 by reacting *sal ammoniac* (ammonium chloride) with *calcined magnesia* (magnesium oxide).
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] It was isolated again by Peter Woulfe in 1767, by Carl Wilhelm Scheele in 1770 and by Joseph Priestley in 1773 and was termed by him 'alkaline air'.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Eleven years later in 1785, Claude Louis Berthollet ascertained its composition.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The production of ammonia from nitrogen in the air (and hydrogen) was invented by Fritz Haber and Robert LeRossignol.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Later, Carl Bosch developed the industrial method for ammonia production (Haber–Bosch process).
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] It was first used on an industrial scale in Germany during World War I, following the allied blockade that cut off the supply of nitrates from Chile.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The ammonia was used to produce explosives to sustain war efforts.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The Nobel Prize in Chemistry 1918 was awarded to Fritz Haber "for the synthesis of ammonia from its elements".
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Before the availability of natural gas, hydrogen as a precursor to ammonia production was produced via the electrolysis of water or using the chloralkali process.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] With the advent of the steel industry in the 20th century, ammonia became a byproduct of the production of coking coal.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] In the US as of 2019, approximately 88% of ammonia was used as fertilisers either as its salts, solutions or anhydrously.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] When applied to soil, it helps provide increased yields of crops such as maize and wheat.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] 30% of agricultural nitrogen applied in the US is in the form of anhydrous ammonia, and worldwide, 110 million tonnes are applied each year.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Solutions of ammonia ranging from 16% to 25% are used in the fermentation industry as a source of nitrogen for microorganisms and to adjust pH during fermentation.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] African countries aim to use their potential to produce renewable ammonia to reduce their dependence on fertiliser imports.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Because of ammonia's vapourisation properties, it is a useful refrigerant.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] It was commonly used before the popularisation of chlorofluorocarbons (Freons).
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Anhydrous ammonia is widely used in industrial refrigeration applications and hockey rinks because of its high energy efficiency and low cost.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] It suffers from the disadvantage of toxicity, and requiring corrosion resistant components, which restricts its domestic and small-scale use.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Along with its use in modern vapour-compression refrigeration it is used in a mixture along with hydrogen and water in absorption refrigerators.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The Kalina cycle, which is of growing importance to geothermal power plants, depends on the wide boiling range of the ammonia–water mixture.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia coolant is also used in the radiators aboard the International Space Station in loops that are used to regulate the internal temperature and enable temperature-dependent experiments.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The ammonia is under sufficient pressure to remain liquid throughout the process.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Single-phase ammonia cooling systems also serve the power electronics in each pair of solar arrays.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The potential importance of ammonia as a refrigerant has increased with the discovery that vented CFCs and HFCs are potent and stable greenhouse gases.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] As early as in 1895, it was known that ammonia was 'strongly antiseptic; it requires 1.4 grams per litre to preserve beef tea (broth).' In one study, anhydrous ammonia destroyed 99.999% of zoonotic bacteria in three types of animal feed, but not silage.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Anhydrous ammonia is currently used commercially to reduce or eliminate microbial contamination of beef.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Lean finely textured beef (popularly known as 'pink slime') in the beef industry is made from fatty beef trimmings (c.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] 50–70% fat) by removing the fat using heat and centrifugation, then treating it with ammonia to kill *E. coli*.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The process was deemed effective and safe by the US Department of Agriculture based on a study that found that the treatment reduces *E. coli* to undetectable levels.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] There have been safety concerns about the process as well as consumer complaints about the taste and smell of ammonia-treated beef.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia has been used as fuel, and is a proposed alternative to fossil fuels and hydrogen, especially in maritime transport.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Being liquid at ambient temperature under its own vapour pressure and having high volumetric and gravimetric energy density, ammonia is considered a suitable carrier for hydrogen, and may be cheaper than direct transport of liquid hydrogen.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Compared to hydrogen, ammonia is easier to store.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Compared to hydrogen as a fuel, ammonia is much more energy efficient, and could be produced, stored and delivered at a much lower cost than hydrogen, which must be kept compressed or as a cryogenic liquid.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The raw energy density of liquid ammonia is 11.5 MJ/L, which is about a third that of diesel.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia can also be converted back to hydrogen to be used to power hydrogen fuel cells, or it may be used directly within high-temperature solid oxide direct ammonia fuel cells to provide efficient power sources that do not emit greenhouse gases.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia to hydrogen conversion can be achieved through the sodium amide process or the catalytic decomposition of ammonia using solid catalysts.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia production currently creates 1.8% of global CO2 emissions.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] 'Green ammonia' is ammonia produced by using green hydrogen (hydrogen produced by electrolysis with electricity from renewable energy), whereas 'blue ammonia' is ammonia produced using blue hydrogen (hydrogen produced by steam methane reforming) where the carbon dioxide has been captured and stored.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] In a world first in 2020, Saudi Arabia shipped 40 metric tons of liquid 'blue ammonia' to Japan for use as a fuel.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] It was produced as a by-product by petrochemical industries, and can be burned without giving off greenhouse gases.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Its energy density by volume is nearly double that of liquid hydrogen.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] If the process of creating it can be scaled up via purely renewable resources, producing green ammonia, it could make a major difference in avoiding climate change.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Green ammonia is considered as a potential fuel for new ships, including future container ships.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia is expected to increase in usage as a fuel source for shipping The IEA forecasts that ammonia will meet approximately 45% of shipping fuel demands by 2050.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] In 2020, the companies DSME and MAN Energy Solutions announced the construction of an ammonia-based ship, DSME plans to commercialise it by 2025.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The use of ammonia as a potential alternative fuel for aircraft jet engines is also being explored.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] In addition, hybrid engine configurations for supersonic aviation employing ammonia fuel have been investigated.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Japan is implementing a plan to develop ammonia co-firing technology that can increase the use of ammonia in power generation, as part of efforts to assist domestic and other Asian utilities to accelerate their transition to carbon neutrality.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] In October 2021, the first International Conference on Fuel Ammonia (ICFA2021) was held.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] In June 2022, IHI Corporation succeeded in reducing greenhouse gases by over 99% during combustion of liquid ammonia in a 2,000-kilowatt-class gas turbine achieving truly CO2-free power generation.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] In July 2022, Quad nations of Japan, the US, Australia and India agreed to promote technological development for clean-burning hydrogen and ammonia as fuels at the security grouping's first energy meeting.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] As of 2022, however, significant amounts of NO*x* are produced.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Nitrous oxide may also be a problem as it is a "*greenhouse gas that is known to possess up to 300 times the Global Warming Potential (GWP) of carbon dioxide*".
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia engines or ammonia motors, using ammonia as a working fluid, have been proposed and occasionally used.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The principle is similar to that used in a fireless locomotive, but with ammonia as the working fluid, instead of steam or compressed air.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia engines were used experimentally in the 19th century by Goldsworthy Gurney in the UK and the St.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Charles Streetcar Line in New Orleans in the 1870s and 1880s, and during World War II ammonia was used to power buses in Belgium.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia is sometimes proposed as a practical alternative to fossil fuel for internal combustion engines.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] However, ammonia cannot be easily used in existing Otto cycle engines because of its very narrow flammability range.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Despite this, several tests have been run.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Its high octane rating of 120 and low flame temperature allows the use of high compression ratios without a penalty of high NO*x* production.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Since ammonia contains no carbon, its combustion cannot produce carbon dioxide, carbon monoxide, hydrocarbons, or soot.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] At high temperature and in the presence of a suitable catalyst, ammonia decomposes into its constituent elements.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Decomposition of ammonia is a slightly endothermic process requiring 23 kJ/mol (5.5 kcal/mol) of ammonia, and yields hydrogen and nitrogen gas.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Rocket engines have also been fuelled by ammonia.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The Reaction Motors XLR99 rocket engine that powered the X-15 hypersonic research aircraft used liquid ammonia.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Although not as powerful as other fuels, it left no soot in the reusable rocket engine, and its density approximately matches the density of the oxidiser, liquid oxygen, which simplified the aircraft's design.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Liquid ammonia is also an attractive alternative to liquid hydrogen as a nuclear-thermal rocket propellant, offering increased thrust (at reduced fuel efficiency).
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The company ACWA Power and the city of Neom have announced the construction of a green hydrogen and ammonia plant in 2020.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia is used to scrub SO2 from the burning of fossil fuels, and the resulting product is converted to ammonium sulfate for use as fertiliser.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia neutralises the nitrogen oxide (NO*x*) pollutants emitted by diesel engines.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] This technology, called SCR (selective catalytic reduction), relies on a vanadia-based catalyst.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia may be used to mitigate gaseous spills of phosgene.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia, as the vapour released by smelling salts, has found significant use as a respiratory stimulant.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia is commonly used in the illegal manufacture of methamphetamine through a Birch reduction.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The Birch method of making methamphetamine is dangerous because the alkali metal and liquid ammonia are both extremely reactive, and the temperature of liquid ammonia makes it susceptible to explosive boiling when reactants are added.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Liquid ammonia is used for treatment of cotton materials, giving properties like mercerisation, using alkalis.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] In particular, it is used for prewashing of wool.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] At standard temperature and pressure, ammonia is less dense than atmosphere and has approximately 45–48% of the lifting power of hydrogen or helium.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia has sometimes been used to fill balloons as a lifting gas.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Because of its relatively high boiling point (compared to helium and hydrogen), ammonia could potentially be refrigerated and liquefied aboard an airship to reduce lift and add ballast (and returned to a gas to add lift and reduce ballast).
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia has been used to darken quartersawn white oak in Arts & Crafts and Mission-style furniture.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia fumes react with the natural tannins in the wood and cause it to change colour.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia is used as an ingredient in various cleaning products, such as Windex (until 2006), in the form of ammonia solution.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The US Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) has set a 15-minute exposure limit for gaseous ammonia of 35 ppm by volume in the environmental air and an 8-hour exposure limit of 25 ppm by volume.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Other organisations have varying exposure levels.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] US Navy Standards [US Bureau of Ships 1962] maximum allowable concentrations (MACs): for continuous exposure (60 days) is 25 ppm; for exposure of 1 hour is 400 ppm.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia is an irritant and irritation increases with concentration; the permissible exposure limit is 25 ppm, and lethal above 500 ppm by volume.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia vapour has a sharp, irritating, pungent odour that acts as a warning of potentially dangerous exposure.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The average odour threshold is 5 ppm, well below any danger or damage.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Exposure to very high concentrations of gaseous ammonia can result in lung damage and death.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia is regulated in the US as a non-flammable gas, but it meets the definition of a material that is toxic by inhalation and requires a hazardous safety permit when transported in quantities greater than 3,500 US gallons (13,000 L; 2,900 imp gal).
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The toxicity of ammonia solutions does not usually cause problems for humans and other mammals because they possess metabolic pathways that prevent ammonia from accumulating in the bloodstream.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia is converted to carbamoyl phosphate by the enzyme carbamoyl phosphate synthetase and then enters the urea cycle, where it is incorporated into amino acids or excreted as urea.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Fish and amphibians lack this internal detoxification mechanism because they normally eliminate ammonia directly into the surrounding water.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] As a result, they are highly sensitive to elevated environmental concentrations: even dilute levels in the water can impede excretion and lead to toxic accumulation.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] For this reason, ammonia in aquatic environments is classified as *dangerous for the environment*.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Atmospheric ammonia also plays a key role in the formation of fine particulate matter.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia is also a constituent of tobacco smoke.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia is present in coking wastewater streams, as a liquid by-product of the production of coke from coal.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] In some cases, the ammonia is discharged to the marine environment where it acts as a pollutant.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The Whyalla Steelworks in South Australia is one example of a coke-producing facility that discharges ammonia into marine waters.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia toxicity is believed to be a cause of otherwise unexplained losses in fish hatcheries.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Excess ammonia may accumulate and cause alteration of metabolism or increases in the body pH of the exposed organism.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] At lower concentrations, around 0.05 mg/L, un-ionised ammonia is harmful to fish species and can result in poor growth and feed conversion rates, reduced fecundity and fertility and increase stress and susceptibility to bacterial infections and diseases.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Exposed to excess ammonia, fish may suffer loss of equilibrium, hyper-excitability, increased respiratory activity and oxygen uptake and increased heart rate.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] At concentrations exceeding 2.0 mg/L, ammonia causes gill and tissue damage, extreme lethargy, convulsions, coma, and death.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Experiments have shown that the lethal concentration for a variety of fish species ranges from 0.2 to 2.0 mg/L.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] During winter, when reduced feeds are administered to aquaculture stock, ammonia levels can be higher.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Lower ambient temperatures reduce the rate of algal photosynthesis so less ammonia is removed by any algae present.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Within an aquaculture environment, especially at large scale, there is no fast-acting remedy to elevated ammonia levels.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Prevention rather than correction is recommended to reduce harm to farmed fish and in open water systems, the surrounding environment.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Similar to propane, anhydrous ammonia boils below room temperature when at atmospheric pressure.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] A storage vessel capable of 250 psi (1.7 MPa) is suitable to contain the liquid.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia is used in numerous different industrial applications requiring carbon or stainless steel storage vessels.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia with at least 0.2% by weight water content is not corrosive to carbon steel.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] NH3 carbon steel construction storage tanks with 0.2% by weight or more of water could last more than 50 years in service.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Experts warn that ammonium compounds not be allowed to come in contact with bases (unless in an intended and contained reaction), as dangerous quantities of ammonia gas could be released.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The hazards of ammonia solutions depend on the concentration: 'dilute' ammonia solutions are usually 5–10% by weight (< 5.62 mol/L); 'concentrated' solutions are usually prepared at >25% by weight.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] A 25% (by weight) solution has a density of 0.907 g/cm3, and a solution that has a lower density will be more concentrated.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The European Union classification of ammonia solutions is given in the table.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The ammonia vapour from concentrated ammonia solutions is severely irritating to the eyes and the respiratory tract, and experts warn that these solutions only be handled in a fume hood.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Saturated ('0.880'–see *§ Properties*) solutions can develop a significant pressure inside a closed bottle in warm weather, and experts also warn that the bottle be opened with care.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] This is not usually a problem for 25% ('0.900') solutions.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Experts warn that ammonia solutions not be mixed with halogens, as toxic and/or explosive products are formed.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Anhydrous ammonia is classified as toxic (**T**) and dangerous for the environment (**N**).
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The gas is flammable (autoignition temperature: 651 °C) and can form explosive mixtures with air (16–25%).
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The permissible exposure limit (PEL) in the United States is 50 ppm (35 mg/m3), while the IDLH concentration is estimated at 300 ppm.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Repeated exposure to ammonia lowers the sensitivity to the smell of the gas: normally the odour is detectable at concentrations of less than 50 ppm, but desensitised individuals may not detect it even at concentrations of 100 ppm.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Anhydrous ammonia corrodes copper- and zinc-containing alloys, which makes brass fittings not appropriate for handling the gas.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Liquid ammonia can also attack rubber and certain plastics.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia reacts violently with the halogens.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Nitrogen triiodide, a primary high explosive, is formed when ammonia comes in contact with iodine.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia causes the explosive polymerisation of ethylene oxide.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] It also forms explosive fulminating compounds with compounds of gold, silver, mercury, germanium or tellurium, and with stibine.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Violent reactions have also been reported with acetaldehyde, hypochlorite solutions, potassium ferricyanide and peroxides.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Ammonia has one of the highest rates of production of any inorganic chemical.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Production is sometimes expressed in terms of "fixed nitrogen".
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Global production was estimated as being 160 million tonnes in 2020 (147 tons of fixed nitrogen).
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] China accounted for 26.5% of that, followed by Russia at 11.0%, the United States at 9.5%, and India at 8.3%.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The Haber process, also called the Haber–Bosch process, is the main industrial procedure for the production of ammonia.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] This reaction is exothermic but disfavored in terms of entropy because four equivalents of reactant gases are converted into two equivalents of product gas.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] However, due to the extremely high kinetic barriers to bond cleavage, high pressures and temperatures are needed to drive the reaction forward.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The Haber Process was first created by the German Chemist Fritz Haber, then developed after a few years by Carl Bosch.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The German chemists Fritz Haber and Carl Bosch developed the process in the first decade of the 20th century, and its improved efficiency over existing methods such as the Birkeland–Eyde and Frank–Caro processes was a major advancement in the industrial production of ammonia.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The Haber process can be combined with steam reforming to produce ammonia with just three chemical inputs: water, natural gas, and atmospheric nitrogen.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Both Haber and Bosch were eventually awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry: Haber in 1918 for ammonia synthesis specifically, and Bosch in 1931 for related contributions to high-pressure chemistry.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The electrochemical synthesis of ammonia involves the reductive formation of lithium nitride, which can be protonated to ammonia, given a proton source.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The first use of this chemistry was reported in 1930, where lithium solutions in ethanol were used to produce ammonia at pressures of up to 1000 bar, with ethanol acting as the proton source.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Beyond simply mediating proton transfer to the nitrogen reduction reaction, ethanol has been found to play a multifaceted role, influencing electrolyte transformations and contributing to the formation of the solid electrolyte interphase, which enhances overall reaction efficiency.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] In 1994, Tsuneto et al. used lithium electrodeposition in tetrahydrofuran to synthesize ammonia at more moderate pressures with reasonable Faradaic efficiency.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Subsequent studies have further explored the ethanol–tetrahydrofuran system for electrochemical ammonia synthesis.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] In 2020, a solvent-agnostic gas diffusion electrode was shown to improve nitrogen transport to the reactive lithium.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] NH3 production rates of up to 30 ± 5 nmol/(s⋅cm2) and Faradaic efficiencies of up to 47.5 ± 4% at ambient temperature and 1 bar pressure were achieved.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] In 2021, it was demonstrated that ethanol could be replaced with a tetraalkyl phosphonium salt.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The study observed NH3 production rates of 53 ± 1 nmol/(s⋅cm2) at 69 ± 1% Faradaic efficiency experiments under 0.5 bar hydrogen and 19.5 bar nitrogen partial pressure at ambient temperature.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] Technology based on this electrochemistry is being developed for commercial fertiliser and fuel production.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] In 2022, ammonia was produced via the lithium mediated process in a continuous-flow electrolyzer also demonstrating the hydrogen gas as proton source.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p01] The study synthesised ammonia at 61 ± 1% Faradaic efficiency at a current density of −6 mA/cm2 at 1 bar and room temperature.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] For example, it is required for the formation of amino acids and nucleic acids, fundamental building blocks of life.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Within a cell, glutamate serves this role.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] In the bloodstream, glutamine is a source of ammonia.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Ammonia is both a metabolic waste and a metabolic input throughout the biosphere.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] It is an important source of nitrogen for living systems.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Although atmospheric nitrogen abounds (more than 75%), few living creatures are capable of using atmospheric nitrogen in its diatomic form, N2 gas.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Therefore, nitrogen fixation is required for the synthesis of amino acids, which are the building blocks of protein.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Some plants rely on ammonia and other nitrogenous wastes incorporated into the soil by decaying matter.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Others, such as nitrogen-fixing legumes, benefit from symbiotic relationships with rhizobia bacteria that create ammonia from atmospheric nitrogen.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] In humans, inhaling ammonia in high concentrations can be fatal.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Exposure to ammonia can cause headaches, edema, impaired memory, seizures and coma as it is neurotoxic in nature.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] In certain organisms, ammonia is produced from atmospheric nitrogen by enzymes called nitrogenases.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] The overall process is called nitrogen fixation.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Intense effort has been directed toward understanding the mechanism of biological nitrogen fixation.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] The scientific interest in this problem is motivated by the unusual structure of the active site of the enzyme, which consists of an Fe7MoS9 ensemble.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Ammonia is also a metabolic product of amino acid deamination catalysed by enzymes such as glutamate dehydrogenase 1.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Ammonia excretion is common in aquatic animals.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] In humans, it is quickly converted to urea (by liver), which is much less toxic, particularly less basic.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] This urea is a major component of the dry weight of urine.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Most reptiles, birds, insects, and snails excrete uric acid solely as nitrogenous waste.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Ammonia plays a role in both normal and abnormal animal physiology.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] It is biosynthesised through normal amino acid metabolism and is toxic in high concentrations.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] The liver converts ammonia to urea through a series of reactions known as the urea cycle.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Liver dysfunction, such as that seen in cirrhosis, may lead to elevated amounts of ammonia in the blood (hyperammonemia).
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Likewise, defects in the enzymes responsible for the urea cycle, such as ornithine transcarbamylase, lead to hyperammonemia.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Hyperammonemia contributes to the confusion and coma of hepatic encephalopathy, as well as the neurological disease common in people with urea cycle defects and organic acidurias.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Ammonia is important for normal animal acid/base balance.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] After formation of ammonium from glutamine, α-ketoglutarate may be degraded to produce two bicarbonate ions, which are then available as buffers for dietary acids.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Ammonium is excreted in the urine, resulting in net acid loss.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Ammonia may itself diffuse across the renal tubules, combine with a hydrogen ion, and thus allow for further acid excretion.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Ammonium ions are a toxic waste product of metabolism in animals.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] In fish and aquatic invertebrates, it is excreted directly into the water.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] In mammals, sharks, and amphibians, it is converted in the urea cycle to urea, which is less toxic and can be stored more efficiently.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] In birds, reptiles, and terrestrial snails, metabolic ammonium is converted into uric acid, which is solid and can therefore be excreted with minimal water loss.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Ammonia has been detected in the atmospheres of the giant planets Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus and Neptune, along with other gases such as methane, hydrogen, and helium.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] The interior of Saturn may include frozen ammonia crystals.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Ammonia was first detected in interstellar space in 1968, based on microwave emissions from the direction of the galactic core.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] This was the first polyatomic molecule to be so detected.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] The sensitivity of the molecule to a broad range of excitations and the ease with which it can be observed in a number of regions has made ammonia one of the most important molecules for studies of molecular clouds.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] The relative intensity of the ammonia lines can be used to measure the temperature of the emitting medium.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] The following isotopic species of ammonia have been detected: NH3,15NH3, NH2D, NHD2, and ND3.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] The detection of triply deuterated ammonia was considered a surprise as deuterium is relatively scarce.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] It is thought that the low-temperature conditions allow this molecule to survive and accumulate.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Since its interstellar discovery, NH3 has proved to be an invaluable spectroscopic tool in the study of the interstellar medium.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] With a large number of transitions sensitive to a wide range of excitation conditions, NH3 has been widely astronomically detected–its detection has been reported in hundreds of journal articles.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Listed below is a sample of journal articles that highlights the range of detectors that have been used to identify ammonia.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] The study of interstellar ammonia has been important to a number of areas of research in the last few decades.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Some of these are delineated below and primarily involve using ammonia as an interstellar thermometer.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] The interstellar abundance for ammonia has been measured for a variety of environments.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] The [NH3]/[H2] ratio has been estimated to range from 10−7 in small dark clouds up to 10−5 in the dense core of the Orion molecular cloud complex.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] The rate constant, *k*, of this reaction depends on the temperature of the environment, with a value of $5.2\times 10^{-6}$ at 10 K.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] The rate constant was calculated from the formula ⁠ $k=a(T/300)^{B}$ ⁠.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Assuming an NH+4 abundance of $3\times 10^{-7}$ and an electron abundance of 10−7 typical of molecular clouds, the formation will proceed at a rate of 1.6×10−9 cm−3s−1 in a molecular cloud of total density 105 cm−3.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] All other proposed formation reactions have rate constants of between two and 13 orders of magnitude smaller, making their contribution to the abundance of ammonia relatively insignificant.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Assuming H2 densities of 105 and [NH2]/[H2] ratio of 10−7, this reaction proceeds at a rate of 2.2×10−12, more than three orders of magnitude slower than the primary reaction above.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] There are 113 total proposed reactions leading to the destruction of NH3.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Of these, 39 were tabulated in extensive tables of the chemistry among C, N and O compounds.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] These calculations assumed the given rate constants and abundances of [NH3]/[H2] = 10−5, [[H3]+]/[H2] = 2×10−5, [HCO+]/[H2] = 2×10−9, and total densities of *n* = 105, typical of cold, dense, molecular clouds.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Clearly, between these two primary reactions, equation (**1**) is the dominant destruction reaction, with a rate ≈10,000 times faster than equation (**2**).
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] This is due to the relatively high abundance of [H3]+.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Radio observations of NH3 from the Effelsberg 100-m Radio Telescope reveal that the ammonia line is separated into two components–a background ridge and an unresolved core.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] The background corresponds well with the locations previously detected CO.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] The 25 m Chilbolton telescope in England detected radio signatures of ammonia in H II regions, HNH2O masers, H–H objects, and other objects associated with star formation.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] A comparison of emission line widths indicates that turbulent or systematic velocities do not increase in the central cores of molecular clouds.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Microwave radiation from ammonia was observed in several galactic objects including W3(OH), Orion A, W43, W51, and five sources in the galactic centre.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] The high detection rate indicates that this is a common molecule in the interstellar medium and that high-density regions are common in the galaxy.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] VLA observations of NH3 in seven regions with high-velocity gaseous outflows revealed condensations of less than 0.1 pc in L1551, S140, and Cepheus A.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Three individual condensations were detected in Cepheus A, one of them with a highly elongated shape.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] They may play an important role in creating the bipolar outflow in the region.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Extragalactic ammonia was imaged using the VLA in IC 342.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] The hot gas has temperatures above 70 K, which was inferred from ammonia line ratios and appears to be closely associated with the innermost portions of the nuclear bar seen in CO.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Based upon temperature and density diagnostics, it is concluded that in general such clumps are probably the sites of massive star formation in an early evolutionary phase prior to the development of an ultracompact HII region.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Absorption at 2.97 micrometres due to solid ammonia was recorded from interstellar grains in the Becklin–Neugebauer Object and probably in NGC 2264-IR as well.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] This detection helped explain the physical shape of previously poorly understood and related ice absorption lines.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] A spectrum of the disk of Jupiter was obtained from the Kuiper Airborne Observatory, covering the 100 to 300 cm−1 spectral range.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Analysis of the spectrum provides information on global mean properties of ammonia gas and an ammonia ice haze.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] A total of 149 dark cloud positions were surveyed for evidence of 'dense cores' by using the (J,K) = (1,1) rotating inversion line of NH3.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] In general, the cores are not spherically shaped, with aspect ratios ranging from 1.1 to 4.4.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] It is also found that cores with stars have broader lines than cores without stars.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Ammonia has been detected in the Draco Nebula and in one or possibly two molecular clouds, which are associated with the high-latitude galactic infrared cirrus.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] The finding is significant because they may represent the birthplaces for the Population I metallicity B-type stars in the galactic halo that could have been borne in the galactic disk.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] By balancing and stimulated emission with spontaneous emission, it is possible to construct a relation between excitation temperature and density.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Moreover, since the transitional levels of ammonia can be approximated by a 2-level system at low temperatures, this calculation is fairly simple.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] This premise can be applied to dark clouds, regions suspected of having extremely low temperatures and possible sites for future star formation.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Detections of ammonia in dark clouds show very narrow lines – indicative not only of low temperatures, but also of a low level of inner-cloud turbulence.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Line ratio calculations provide a measurement of cloud temperature that is independent of previous CO observations.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] The ammonia observations were consistent with CO measurements of rotation temperatures of ≈10 K.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] With this, densities can be determined, and have been calculated to range between 104 and 105 cm−3 in dark clouds.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Mapping of NH3 gives typical clouds sizes of 0.1 pc and masses near 1 solar mass.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] These cold, dense cores are the sites of future star formation.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Ultra-compact HII regions are among the best tracers of high-mass star formation.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] The dense material surrounding UCHII regions is likely primarily molecular.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Since a complete study of massive star formation necessarily involves the cloud from which the star formed, ammonia is an invaluable tool in understanding this surrounding molecular material.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Since this molecular material can be spatially resolved, it is possible to constrain the heating/ionising sources, temperatures, masses, and sizes of the regions.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Doppler-shifted velocity components allow for the separation of distinct regions of molecular gas that can trace outflows and hot cores originating from forming stars.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Ammonia has been detected in external galaxies, and by simultaneously measuring several lines, it is possible to directly measure the gas temperature in these galaxies.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] Line ratios imply that gas temperatures are warm (≈50 K), originating from dense clouds with sizes of tens of parsecs.
[src:ammonia/ammonia-p02] This picture is consistent with the picture within our Milky Way galaxy – hot dense molecular cores form around newly forming stars embedded in larger clouds of molecular material on the scale of several hundred parsecs (giant molecular clouds; GMCs).
